Faitour: A doer or actor; particularly, an evil doer; a scoundrel.
Frontier: To constitute or form a frontier; to have a frontier; -- with on.
Freezing: Tending to freeze; for freezing; hence, cold or distant in manner.
Faradic: Of or pertaining to Michael Faraday, the distinguished electrician; -- applied especially to induced currents of electricity, as produced by certain forms of inductive apparatus, on account of Faraday's investigations of their laws.
Flutist: A performer on the flute; a flautist.
Fan palm: Any palm tree having fan-shaped or radiate leaves; as the Chamærops humilis of Southern Europe; the species of Sabal and Thrinax in the West Indies, Florida, etc.; and especially the great talipot tree (Corypha umbraculifera) of Ceylon and Malaya. The leaves of the latter are often eighteen feet long and fourteen wide, and are used for umbrellas, tents, and roofs. When cut up, they are used for books and manuscripts.
Forefend: To hinder; to fend off; to avert; to prevent the approach of; to forbid or prohibit. See Forfend.
firelighter: (a piece of) a substance that burns easily and can be used to start a coal or coke fire.
Fractional: Of or pertaining to fractions or a fraction; constituting a fraction; as, fractional numbers.
Fixedly: In a fixed, stable, or constant manner.
Footfall: A setting down of the foot; a footstep; the sound of a footstep.
&Verbar;Farandole: A rapid dance in six-eight time in which a large number join hands and dance in various figures, sometimes moving from room to room. It originated in Provence.
Foundation: The act of founding, fixing, establishing, or beginning to erect.
Faintness: The state of being faint; loss of strength, or of consciousness, and self-control.
Flagitate: To importune; to demand fiercely or with passion.
&Verbar;Fieri facias: A judicial writ that lies for one who has recovered in debt or damages, commanding the sheriff that he cause to be made of the goods, chattels, or real estate of the defendant, the sum claimed.
Foreknow: To have previous knowledge of; to know beforehand.
Fascicule: A small bunch or bundle; a fascicle; as, a fascicule of fibers, hairs, or spines.
fringepod: An annual herb having pinnatifid basal leaves and slender racemes of small white flowers followed by one-seeded winged silicles.
Firing pin: In the breech mechanism of a firearm, the pin which strikes the head of the cartridge and explodes it.
Funiliform: Resembling a cord in toughness and flexibility, as the roots of some endogenous trees.
fanwort: a common aquatic plant (Cabomba caroliniana) of eastern North America having floating and submerged leaves and white yellow-spotted flowers.
Fawn-colored: Of the color of a fawn; light yellowish brown.
Fondness: The quality or state of being fond; foolishness.
Fantasticism: The quality of being fantastical; fancifulness; whimsicality.
Filicic: Pertaining to, or derived from, ferns; as, filicic acid.
Foolery: The practice of folly; the behavior of a fool; absurdity.
Fragile: Easily broken; brittle; frail; delicate; easily destroyed.
fastbreak: a rapid dash to get a shot at one's own basket as soon as possible after taking possession of the ball; -- often occurring after the opposing team has shot at their basket.
Frequenter: One who frequents; one who often visits, or resorts to customarily.
Fissuration: The act of dividing or opening; the state of being fissured.
Fitly: In a fit manner; suitably; properly; conveniently; as, a maxim fitly applied.
frailty: The condition or quality of being frail, physically, mentally, or morally; frailness; infirmity; weakness of resolution; liableness to be deceived or seduced.
Forerun: To turn before; to precede; to be in advance of (something following).
Filing: A fragment or particle rubbed off by the act of filing; as, iron filings.
Favorless: Unfavored; not regarded with favor; having no countenance or support.
founded: based; -- often used as combining terms; as, well-founded suspicions.
Festal: Of or pertaining to a holiday or a feast; joyous; festive.
Fugitive: One who flees from pursuit, danger, restraint, service, duty, etc.; a deserter; as, a fugitive from justice.
Fibrocartilage: A kind of cartilage with a fibrous matrix and approaching fibrous connective tissue in structure.
Fomorian: (Irish) one of a group of sea demons sometimes associated with the hostile power of nature.
Filamentous: Like a thread; consisting of threads or filaments.
Freebooter: One who plunders or pillages without the authority of national warfare; a member of a predatory band; a pillager; a buccaneer; a sea robber.
Fullery: The place or the works where the fulling of cloth is carried on.
Fragrance: The quality of being fragrant; sweetness of smell; a sweet smell; a pleasing odor; perfume.
Flatlong: With the flat side downward; not edgewise.
forged: Not genuine; counterfeit; -- used mostly of signatures and documents.  See forge, v. t., 4.
Fortread: To tread down; to trample upon.
Fireproofing: The act or process of rendering anything incombustible; also, the materials used in the process.
Febrifugal: Having the quality of mitigating or curing fever.
Festival: Pertaining to a fest; festive; festal; appropriate to a festival; joyous; mirthful.
Fangot: A quantity of wares, as raw silk, etc., from one hundred weight.
Fiend: An implacable or malicious foe; one who is diabolically wicked or cruel; an infernal being; -- applied specifically to the devil or a demon.
Flagman: One who makes signals with a flag.
Forestaller: One who forestalls; esp., one who forestalls the market.
Filiciform: Shaped like a fern or like the parts of a fern leaf.
Flexural: Of, pertaining to, or resulting from, flexure; of the nature of, or characterized by, flexure; as, flexural elasticity.
Forcible-feeble: Seemingly vigorous, but really weak or insipid.
Flinty: Consisting of, composed of, abounding in, or resembling, flint; as, a flinty rock; flinty ground; a flinty heart.
Fugle: To maneuver; to move hither and thither.
&Verbar;Fovea: A slight depression or pit; a fossa.
Ferruginated: Having the color or properties of the rust of iron.
Ferulic: Pertaining to, or derived from, asafetida (Ferula asafœtida); as, ferulic acid.
Feere: A consort, husband or wife; a companion; a fere.
frank: To send by public conveyance free of expense.
&Verbar;Flatus: A breath; a puff of wind.
Facingly: In a facing manner or position.
Fumarole: A hole or spot in a volcanic or other region, from which fumes issue.
Firewarden: An officer who has authority to direct in the extinguishing of fires, or to order what precautions shall be taken against fires; -- called also fireward.
Faced: Having (such) a face, or (so many) faces; as, smooth-faced, two-faced.
Frump: A contemptuous speech or piece of conduct; a gibe or flout.
Ferrary: The art of working in iron.
filbert: The fruit of the Corylus Avellana or Corylus maxima, also called the hazel; the hazelnut.  It is an oval nut, containing a kernel that has a mild, farinaceous, oily taste, agreeable to the palate.
Fanion: A small flag sometimes carried at the head of the baggage of a brigade.
Founderous: Difficult to travel; likely to trip one up; as, a founderous road.
Flip: To become insane or irrational; -- often used with out; as, seeing her mother killed made the girl flip out.
Facet: To cut facets or small faces upon; as, to facet a diamond.
Ferraro: Geraldine Anne Ferraro, a United States politician.  Born in 1935, she was a congresswoman from New York in the United States Congress from 1978 to 1984, and ran unsuccessfully in 1984 a candidate for Vice President of the United States, with Walter Mondale as the Presidential candidate.  She was the first woman to be nominated by a major U. S. political party for the office of Vice President.
Facer: One who faces; one who puts on a false show; a bold-faced person.
Fabiana: a genus of South and Central American heathlike evergreen shrubs.
Ferrara: A sword bearing the mark of one of the Ferrara family of Italy. These swords were highly esteemed in England and Scotland in the 16th and 17th centuries.
Ferris wheel: An amusement device consisting of a giant power-driven vertically oriented steel wheel, revolvable on its horizontal stationary axle, and carrying a number of balanced passenger cars or open seats around its rim; the seats are suspended so as to remain horizontal as the wheel rotates, and, depending on the size of the wheel, the passengers when they reach the top may have a grand vista of the surrounding area; -- so called after G. W. G. Ferris, American engineer, who erected the first of its kind for the World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago in 1893.
Full-blooded: Having a full supply of blood.
Forego: To go before; to precede; -- used especially in the present and past participles.
Forwarding: The act of one who forwards; the act or occupation of transmitting merchandise or other property for others.
Feathery: Pertaining to, or resembling, feathers; covered with, or as with, feathers; as, feathery spray or snow.
Forming: The act or process of giving form or shape to anything; as, in shipbuilding, the exact shaping of partially shaped timbers.
Frostfish: The tomcod; -- so called because it is abundant on the New England coast in autumn at about the commencement of frost. See Tomcod.
Forenoon: The early part of the day, from morning to meridian, or noon.
&Verbar;Fasti: The Roman calendar, which gave the days for festivals, courts, etc., corresponding to a modern almanac.
Fyllot: A rebated cross, formerly used as a secret emblem, and a common ornament. It is also called gammadion, and swastika.
fleer: To make a wry face in contempt, or to grin in scorn; to deride; to sneer; to mock; to gibe; as, to fleer and flout.
Fescennine: Pertaining to, or resembling, the Fescennines.
Fluoranthene: A white crystalline hydrocarbon C15H10, of a complex structure, found as one ingredient of the higher boiling portion of coal tar.
Fatimite: Descended from Fatima, the daughter and only child of Mohammed.
Fluid: A fluid substance; a body whose particles move easily among themselves.
Fasciole: A band of minute tubercles, bearing modified spines, on the shells of spatangoid sea urchins. See Spatangoidea.
Fly amanita: A poisonous mushroom (Amanita muscaria, syn. Agaricus muscarius), having usually a bright red or yellowish cap covered with irregular white spots. It has a distinct volva at the base, generally an upper ring on the stalk, and white spores. Called also fly agaric, deadly amanita.
Ferricyanic: Pertaining to, or derived from, a ferricyanide.
Foot candle: The amount of illumination produced by a standard candle at a distance of one foot.
firebreak: a narrow field that has been cleared to check the spread of a prairie fire or forest fire.
&Verbar;Frater: A monk; also, a frater house.
Fair-weather: Made or done in pleasant weather, or in circumstances involving but little exposure or sacrifice; as, a fair-weather voyage.
Frumenty: Food made of hulled wheat boiled in milk, with sugar, plums, etc.
Floriated: Having floral ornaments; as, floriated capitals of Gothic pillars.
Fu: A department in China comprising several hsein; also, the chief city of a department; -- often forming the last part of a name; as, Paoting-fu.
Futility: The quality of being talkative; talkativeness; loquaciousness; loquacity.
full-bosomed: having a pronounced womanly shape, with well-developed breasts.
&Verbar;Feroher: A symbol of the solar deity, found on monuments exhumed in Babylon, Nineveh, etc.
Foin: A pass in fencing; a lunge.
Flashboard: A board placed temporarily upon a milldam, to raise the water in the pond above its usual level; a flushboard.
Fortieth: One of forty equal parts into which one whole is divided; the quotient of a unit divided by forty; one next in order after the thirty-ninth.
Fair-leader: A block, or ring, serving as a guide for the running rigging or for any rope.
Fenian: Pertaining to Fenians or to Fenianism.
Feldspathic: Pertaining to, or consisting of, feldspar.
Friar: A brother or member of any religious order, but especially of one of the four mendicant orders, viz: (a) Minors, Gray Friars, or Franciscans. (b) Augustines. (c) Dominicans or Black Friars. (d) White Friars or Carmelites. See these names in the Vocabulary.
Feigned: Not real or genuine; pretended; counterfeit; insincere; false.
Frangulin: A yellow crystalline dyestuff, regarded as a glucoside, extracted from a species (Rhamnus Frangula) of the buckthorn; -- called also rhamnoxanthin.
Frangulic: Pertaining to, or drived from, frangulin, or a species (Rhamnus Frangula) of the buckthorn.
Funereal: Suiting a funeral; pertaining to burial; solemn; as, at a funereal pace.
foxhole: a small pit in the ground for individual shelter against enemy fire.
Flatter: To use flattery or insincere praise.
Fish-tackle: A tackle or purchase used to raise the flukes of the anchor up to the gunwale. The block used is called the fish-block.
Flatten: To become or grow flat, even, depressed, dull, vapid, spiritless, or depressed below pitch.
&Verbar;Fleuron: A flower-shaped ornament, esp. one terminating an object or forming one of a series, as a knob of a cover to a dish, or a flower-shaped part in a necklace.
Fluorine: A non-metallic, gaseous element of atomic number 9, strongly acid or negative, and associated with chlorine, bromine, and iodine, in the halogen group of which it is the first member. It always occurs combined, is very active chemically, and possesses such an avidity for most elements, and silicon especially, that it can neither be prepared nor kept in glass vessels, but may be contained in lead vessels. If set free it immediately attacks a containing glass vessel, so that it was not isolated until 1886. It is a pungent, corrosive, colorless gas. Symbol F. Atomic weight 19.00.
fieldmouse: any nocturnal Old World mouse of the genus Apodemus inhabing woods and fields and gardens.
Funnelform: Having the form of a funnel, or tunnel; that is, expanding gradually from the bottom upward, as the corolla of some flowers; infundibuliform.
forecasting: The process of calculating and predicting future events, usually based on extrapolation from past experience, and with varying degress of uncertainty.
Foliole: One of the distinct parts of a compound leaf; a leaflet.
Fulling: The process of cleansing, shrinking, and thickening cloth by moisture, heat, and pressure.
&Verbar;Finis: An end; conclusion. It is often placed at the end of a book.
fizzing: Hissing and bubbling, like a carbonated beverage.
Fibrillation: The state of being reduced to fibers.
Finial: The knot or bunch of foliage, or foliated ornament, that forms the upper extremity of a pinnacle in Gothic architecture; sometimes, the pinnacle itself.
footsore: Having sore or tender feet, as by reason of much walking; as, foot-sore cattle.
Fuegian: Of or pertaining to Terra del Fuego.
Fother: To stop (a leak in a ship at sea) by drawing under its bottom a thrummed sail, so that the pressure of the water may force it into the crack.
fedayee: a member of an Arab paramilitary organization, predominantly Palestinian, which performs commando raids, especially against Israel or Israeli targets.  Usually used in the plural.
Foreignness: The quality of being foreign; remoteness; want of relation or appropriateness.
Futuritial: Relating to what is to come; pertaining to futurity; future.
Felicity: The state of being happy; blessedness; blissfulness; enjoyment of good.
Falsism: That which is evidently false; an assertion or statement the falsity of which is plainly apparent; -- opposed to truism.
Frangipani: A perfume derived from, or imitating the odor of, the flower of the red jasmine, a West Indian tree of the genus Plumeria.
Falcon: One of a family (Falconidæ) of raptorial birds, characterized by a short, hooked beak, strong claws, and powerful flight.
&Verbar;Faham: The leaves of an orchid (Angraecum fragrans), of the islands of Bourbon and Mauritius, used (in France) as a substitute for Chinese tea.
&Verbar;Flor\u00e9al: The eight month of the French republican calendar. It began April 20, and ended May 19. See Vendémiare.
Fruiterer: One who deals in fruit; a seller of fruits.
&Verbar;Fusain: Fine charcoal of willow wood, used as a drawing implement.
Fogy: A dull old fellow; a person behind the times, over-conservative, or slow; -- usually preceded by old; an old fogy.
Foge: The Cornish name for a forge used for smelting tin.
Fuzzle: To make drunk; to intoxicate; to fuddle.
&Verbar;Fuero: A code; a charter; a grant of privileges.
Fulani: The language of the Fulani people, a member of the Niger-Congo family of languages.
fractionation: the act or process of separating a mixture into portions of different composition, as in distillation or fractional crystallization.
Fancy-free: Free from the power of love.
Frouzy: Fetid, musty; rank; disordered and offensive to the smell or sight; slovenly; dingy. See Frowzy.
Farfetch: Anything brought from far, or brought about with studious care; a deep strategem.
Forefoot: One of the anterior feet of a quadruped or multiped; -- usually written fore foot.
Fabulous: Feigned, as a story or fable; related in fable; devised; invented; not real; fictitious; as, a fabulous description; a fabulous hero.
Fumigate: To apply smoke to; to expose to smoke or vapor; to purify, or free from infection, by the use of smoke or vapors.
Federative: Uniting in a league; forming a confederacy; federal.
Fritter: To cut, as meat, into small pieces, for frying.
flippers: A type of shoe with a paddle-like front extending well beyond the end of the toe, used an aid in swimming (especially underwater).
Forecastle: A short upper deck forward, formerly raised like a castle, to command an enemy's decks.
feedback: the process in which part of the output of a system is returned to its input.
Faren: p. p. of Fare, v. i.
&Verbar;Fidia: A genus of small beetles, of which one species (the grapevine Fidia, F. longipes) is very injurious to vines in America.
Forefeel: To feel beforehand; to have a presentiment of.
Forgetter: One who forgets; a heedless person.
Floating charge: A charge, lien, etc., that successively attaches to such assets as a person may have from time to time, leaving him more or less free to dispose of or encumber them as if no such charge or lien existed.
Flanged: Having a flange or flanges; as, a flanged wheel.
fealty: Fidelity to one's lord; the feudal obligation by which the tenant or vassal was bound to be faithful to his lord; the special oath by which this obligation was assumed; fidelity to a superior power, or to a government; loyality.  It is no longer the practice to exact the performance of fealty, as a feudal obligation.
Fumidity: The state of being fumid; smokiness.
flowerbed: a bed in which flowers are growing.
Ferrumination: The soldering or uniting of metals.
Feverous: Affected with fever or ague; feverish.
Figment: An invention; a fiction; something feigned or imagined.
&Verbar;Favosites: A genus of fossil corals abundant in the Silurian and Devonian rocks, having polygonal cells with perforated walls.
Flinger: One who flings; one who jeers.
Flambeau: A flaming torch, esp. one made by combining together a number of thick wicks invested with a quick-burning substance (anciently, perhaps, wax; in modern times, pitch or the like); hence, any torch.
Foots: The settlings of oil, molasses, etc., at the bottom of a barrel or hogshead.
Four-cycle: A four-stroke cycle, as the Otto cycle, for an internal-combustion engine.
Footy: Having foots, or settlings; as, footy oil, molasses, etc.
Formicary: The nest or dwelling of a swarm of ants; an ant-hill.
Fallfish: A fresh-water fish of the United States (Semotilus bullaris); -- called also silver chub, and Shiner. The name is also applied to other allied species.
Footprint: The impression of the foot; a trace or footmark; as, “Footprints of the Creator.”
Foodful: Full of food; supplying food; fruitful; fertile.
Furtive: Stolen; obtained or characterized by stealth; sly; secret; stealthy; as, a furtive look.
Frictional: Relating to friction; moved by friction; produced by friction; as, frictional electricity.
Fawn: A servile cringe or bow; mean flattery; sycophancy.
Faultiness: Quality or state of being faulty.
Freya: The daughter of Njörd, and goddess of love and beauty; the Scandinavian Venus; -- in Teutonic myths confounded with Frigga, but in Scandinavian, distinct.
Functional: Pertaining to, or connected with, a function or duty; official.
Foul: An entanglement; a collision, as in a boat race.
Fiddlewood: The wood of several West Indian trees, mostly of the genus Citharexylum.
Four: The sum of four units; four units or objects.
Fan-tailed: Having an expanded, or fan-shaped, tail; as, the fan-tailed pigeon.
Fingering: The act or process of handling or touching with the fingers.
Farse: An addition to, or a paraphrase of, some part of the Latin service in the vernacular; -- common in English before the Reformation.
Frolicly: In a frolicsome manner; with mirth and gayety.
Foreignism: Anything peculiar to a foreign language or people; a foreign idiom or custom.
Figurative: Representing by a figure, or by resemblance; typical; representative.
Factor: To resolve (a quantity) into its factors.
fetichism: The doctrine or practice of belief in fetiches.
Filarial: Of, pertaining to, or caused by, filariæ and allied parasitic worms.
Flabellinerved: Having many nerves diverging radiately from the base; -- said of a leaf.
Fibrolite: A silicate of alumina, of fibrous or columnar structure. It is like andalusite in composition; -- called also sillimanite, and bucholizite.
Fascet: A wire basket on the end of a rod to carry glass bottles, etc., to the annealing furnace; also, an iron rod to be thrust into the mouths of bottles, and used for the same purpose; -- called also pontee and punty.
-form: A suffix used to denote in the form or shape of, resembling, etc.; as, valiform; oviform.
Forestal: Of or pertaining to forests; as, forestal rights.
Fireboard: A chimney board or screen to close a fireplace when not in use.
Forgive: To give wholly; to make over without reservation; to resign.
Forespurrer: One who rides before; a harbinger.
Fieriness: The quality of being fiery; heat; acrimony; irritability; as, a fieriness of temper.
Flexor: A muscle which bends or flexes any part; as, the flexors of the arm or the hand; -- opposed to extensor.
Fleabane: One of various plants, supposed to have efficacy in driving away fleas. They belong, for the most part, to the genera Conyza, Erigeron, and Pulicaria.
Forestay: A large, strong rope, reaching from the foremast head to the bowsprit, to support the mast. See Illust. under Ship.
Freeness: The state or quality of being free; freedom; liberty; openness; liberality; gratuitousness.
Formell: The female of a hawk or falcon.
Foot valve: A suction valve or check valve at the lower end of a pipe; esp., such a valve in a steam-engine condenser opening to the air pump.
Fallible: Liable to fail, mistake, or err; liable to deceive or to be deceived; as, all men are fallible; our opinions and hopes are fallible.
free-thinking: inclined to forms one's own opinions rather than depend upon authority, especially about social and religious issues; exhibiting boldness of speculation; skeptical of authority.
Figural: Represented by figure or delineation; consisting of figures; as, figural ornaments.
Flippantness: State or quality of being flippant.
Forward: To help onward; to advance; to promote; to accelerate; to quicken; to hasten; as, to forward the growth of a plant; to forward one in improvement.
Fatling: A calf, lamb, kid, or other young animal fattened for slaughter; a fat animal; -- said of such animals as are used for food.
Flagon: A vessel with a narrow mouth, used for holding and conveying liquors. It is generally larger than a bottle, and of leather or stoneware rather than of glass.
Frigorific: Causing cold; producing or generating cold.
flatwork: Ironing that can be done mechanically.
Fielding: The act of playing as a fielder.
Footnote: A note of reference or comment at the foot{4} of a page.
flyleaf: A blank leaf in the front of back or a book.
Flustration: The act of flustrating; confusion; flurry.
Frog: To ornament or fasten (a coat, etc.) with trogs. See Frog, n., 4.
Feodality: Feudal tenure; the feudal system. See Feudality.
Folkland: Land held in villenage, being distributed among the folk, or people, at the pleasure of the lord of the manor, and resumed at his discretion. Not being held by any assurance in writing, it was opposed to bookland or charter land, which was held by deed.
Fishiness: The state or quality of being fishy or fishlike.
Fanciful: Full of fancy; guided by fancy, rather than by reason and experience; whimsical; as, a fanciful man forms visionary projects.
Footbreadth: The breadth of a foot; -- used as a measure.
Free coinage: In the fullest sense, the conversion of bullion (of any specified metal) into legal-tender coins for any person who chooses to bring it to the mint; in a modified sense, such coinage when done at a fixed charge proportionate to the cost of the operation.
Franklinite: A kind of mineral of the spinel group.
&Verbar;Fr\u00e4ulein: In Germany, a young lady; an unmarried woman; -- as a title, equivalent to Miss.
Frill: A ruffing of a bird's feathers from cold.
Firmer-chisel: A chisel, thin in proportion to its width. It has a tang to enter the handle instead of a socket for receiving it.
Fight: A battle; an engagement; a contest in arms; a combat; a violent conflict or struggle for victory, between individuals or between armies, ships, or navies, etc.
&Verbar;Fausse-braye: A second rampart, exterior to, and parallel to, the main rampart, and considerably below its level.
Frontiersman: A man living on the frontier.
fact-finding: designed to find information or ascertain facts; as, a fact-finding committee.
Forbiddance: The act of forbidding; prohibition; command or edict against a thing.
Fitz: A son; -- used in compound names, to indicate paternity, esp. of the illegitimate sons of kings and princes of the blood; as, Fitzroy, the son of the king; Fitzclarence, the son of the duke of Clarence.
Foreland: A promontory or cape; a headland; as, the North and South Foreland in Kent, England.
Foolhardihood: The state of being foolhardy; foolhardiness.
&Verbar;Fiasco: A complete or ridiculous failure, esp. of a musical performance, or of any pretentious undertaking.
Fortunately: In a fortunate manner; luckily; successfully; happily.
Flunky: A contemptuous name for a liveried servant or a footman.
Fortification: The act of fortifying; the art or science of fortifying places in order to defend them against an enemy.
Floaty: Swimming on the surface; buoyant; light.
Fabaceous: Having the nature of a bean; like a bean.
flagpole: A pole used to display a flag.
Feathered: Clothed, covered, or fitted with (or as with) feathers or wings; as, a feathered animal; a feathered arrow.
flamethrower: a weapon that squirts ignited liquid or gelatinous fuel for several yards.
Fertilely: In a fertile or fruitful manner.
Forsay: To forbid; to renounce; to forsake; to deny.
&Verbar;Fenes-tella: Any small windowlike opening or recess, esp. one to show the relics within an altar, or the like.
Forceps: A pair of pinchers, or tongs; an instrument for grasping, holding firmly, or exerting traction upon, bodies which it would be inconvenient or impracticable to seize with the fingers, especially one for delicate operations, as those of watchmakers, surgeons, accoucheurs, dentists, etc.
&Verbar;Fadaise: A vapid or meaningless remark; a commonplace; nonsense.
Forerunner: A messenger sent before to give notice of the approach of others; a harbinger; a sign foreshowing something; a prognostic; as, the forerunner of a fever.
Fub: To put off by trickery; to cheat.
Floscularian: One of a group of stalked rotifers, having ciliated tentacles around the lobed disk.
Formalist: One overattentive to forms, or too much confined to them; esp., one who rests in external religious forms, or observes strictly the outward forms of worship, without possessing the life and spirit of religion.
&Verbar;Facto: In fact; by the act or fact.
Fluoroscope: An instrument for observing or exhibiting fluorescence.
Faldstool: A folding stool, or portable seat, made to fold up in the manner of a camo stool. It was formerly placed in the choir for a bishop, when he offciated in any but his own cathedral church.
futurology: Studies projecting or predicting the future based on current trends.
Fiddle-shaped: Inversely ovate, with a deep hollow on each side.
french fries: Strips of potatoes, usually cut with a rectangular cross-section, cooked by immersing in hot fat or oil.
Footfight: A conflict by persons on foot; -- distinguished from a fight on horseback.
Fritinancy: A chirping or creaking, as of a cricket.
Frequency: The condition of returning frequently; occurrence often repeated; common occurence; as, the frequency of crimes; the frequency of miracles.
Fray: A fret or chafe, as in cloth; a place injured by rubbing.
Forging: The act of shaping metal by hammering or pressing.
Fluting: Decoration by means of flutes or channels; a flute, or flutes collectively; as, the fluting of a column or pilaster; the fluting of a lady's ruffle.
Feese: The short run before a leap.
Fluoroscopy: Examination of an object, as the human body, by exposing it to the X rays and observing the shadow cast upon a fluorescent screen; cryptoscopy.
Formalism: The practice or the doctrine of strict adherence to, or dependence on, external forms, esp. in matters of religion.

Fail: Miscarriage; failure; deficiency; fault; -- mostly superseded by failure or failing, except in the phrase without fail.
Figurante: A female figurant; esp., a ballet girl.
Flipe: To turn inside out, or with the leg part back over the foot, as a stocking in pulling off or for putting on.
Fillip: A jerk of the finger forced suddenly from the thumb; a smart blow.
Flashy: Dazzling for a moment; making a momentary show of brilliancy; transitorily bright.
Fee: To reward for services performed, or to be performed; to recompense; to hire or keep in hire; hence, to bribe.
Ferranti cables: A form of conductor, designed by Ferranti, for currents of high potential, and consisting of concentric tubes of copper separated by an insulating material composed of paper saturated with black mineral wax.
Fishwoman: A woman who retails fish; a female fishmonger.
Frenchify: To make French; to infect or imbue with the manners or tastes of the French; to Gallicize.
Feculent: Foul with extraneous or impure substances; abounding with sediment or excrementitious matter; muddy; thick; turbid.
Few: Not many; small, limited, or confined in number; -- indicating a small portion of units or individuals constituting a whole; often, by ellipsis of a noun, a few people.
Feu: A free and gratuitous right to lands made to one for service to be performed by him; a tenure where the vassal, in place of military services, makes a return in grain or in money.
Fiery: Consisting of, containing, or resembling, fire; as, the fiery gulf of Etna; a fiery appearance.
Formedon: A writ of right for a tenant in tail in case of a discontinuance of the estate tail. This writ has been abolished.
Fust: To become moldy; to smell ill.
Fuss: To be overbusy or unduly anxious about trifles; to make a bustle or ado.
Frigatoon: A Venetian vessel, with a square stern, having only a mainmast, jigger mast, and bowsprit; also a sloop of war ship-rigged.
frill: To shake or shiver as with cold; as, the hawk frills.
Flurry: To put in a state of agitation; to excite or alarm.
Funambulate: To walk or to dance on a rope.
Fuse: A wire, bar, or strip of fusible metal inserted for safety in an electric circuit.  When the current increases beyond a certain safe strength, the metal melts, interrupting the circuit and thereby preventing possibility of damage.  It serves the same function as a circuit breaker.
Fudge: A kind of soft candy composed of sugar or maple sugar, milk, and butter, and often chocolate or nuts, boiled and stirred to a proper consistency.
&Verbar;Fides: Faith personified as a goddess; the goddess of faith.
fizz: To make a hissing sound, such as that of a burning fuse or a bubbling carbonated beverage.
Faucet: A fixture for drawing a liquid, as water, molasses, oil, etc., from a pipe, cask, or other vessel, in such quantities as may be desired; -- called also tap, and cock. It consists of a tubular spout, stopped with a movable plug, spigot, valve, or slide.
&Verbar;Fornix: An arch or fold; as, the fornix, or vault, of the cranium; the fornix, or reflection, of the conjuctiva.
Free-handed: Open-handed; liberal; given or giving freely or liberally; as, a freehanded host.
fetterbush: An ornamental evergreen shrub (Pieris floribunda) of the Southeastern U. S. having small white bell-shaped flowers.
Freewheel: Of a freewheel cycle, to run on while the pedals are held still.
Finishing: Tending to complete or to render fit for the market or for use.
Fassaite: A variety of pyroxene, from the valley of Fassa, in the Tyrol.
flavour: same as flavor, v. and n..
Fragmentariness: The quality or property of being in fragments, or broken pieces; incompleteness; want of continuity.
Frondation: The act of stripping, as trees, of leaves or branches; a kind of pruning.
Furfuran: A colorless, oily substance, C4H4O, obtained by distilling certain organic substances, as pine wood, salts of pyromucic acid, etc.; -- called also tetraphenol.
Fairness: The state of being fair, or free form spots or stains, as of the skin; honesty, as of dealing; candor, as of an argument, etc.
Foppery: The behavior, dress, or other indication of a fop; coxcombry; affectation of show; showy folly.
&Verbar;Fanega: A dry measure in Spain and Spanish America, varying from 1&unr_; to 2&unr_; bushels; also, a measure of land.
Feminization: The act of feminizing, or the state of being feminized.
fluoridate: To subject to fluoridation, as of water; to add fluoride to.
Foutra: A fig; -- a word of contempt.
Futureless: Without prospect of betterment in the future.
fattened: fed until grown and ready for slaughter or for sale in the market; -- of market animals.
Flyaway: Disposed to fly away; flighty; unrestrained; light and free; -- used of both persons and things.
Flotsam: Goods lost by shipwreck, and floating on the sea; -- in distinction from jetsam or jetson.
Frisker: One who frisks; one who leaps of dances in gayety; a wanton; an inconstant or unsettled person.
Flabbiness: Quality or state of being flabby.
Ferrocyanic: Pertaining to, derived from, or designating, a ferrocyanide.
Frisket: The light frame which holds the sheet of paper to the tympan in printing.
Fragment: A part broken off; a small, detached portion; an imperfect part; as, a fragment of an ancient writing.
&Verbar;Fructification: The act of forming or producing fruit; the act of fructifying, or rendering productive of fruit; fecundation.
Fisticuff: A cuff or blow with the fist or hand
field-test: to test something in the field, i. e. under the actual conditions under which it will be used; as, The Army field-tested the new tanks.  Used in contrast with testing in a laboratory or under controlled conditions.
&Verbar;Fumatorium: An air-tight compartment in which vapor may be generated to destroy germs or insects; esp., the apparatus used to destroy San José scale on nursery stock, with hydrocyanic acid vapor.
foregone: past; -- used of time; as, foregone summers.  Contrassted to present.
fairground: an open area for holding fairs or exhibitions or circuses.  Often used in plural.
football: An inflated ball to be kicked in sport, usually made in India rubber, or a bladder incased in Leather.
Fossilized: Converted into a fossil; antiquated; firmly fixed in views or opinions.
Flummery: A light kind of food, formerly made of flour or meal; a sort of pap.
Flax-plant: A plant in new Zealand (Phormium tenax), allied to the lilies and aloes. The leaves are two inches wide and several feet long, and furnish a fiber which is used for making ropes, mats, and coarse cloth.
fiddledeedee: An exclamatory word or phrase, equivalent to nonsense!
Feasible: Capable of being done, executed, or effected; practicable.
Feign: To give a mental existence to, as to something not real or actual; to imagine; to invent; hence, to pretend; to form and relate as if true.
fernless: devoid of ferns.  Opposite of ferned.
faze: To cause to become disconcerted or disturbed.  A variant form of Feeze.
Forfeit: In the condition of being forfeited; subject to alienation.
Fleming: A native or inhabitant of Flanders.
Fire: To take fire; to be kindled; to kindle.
Fucate: Painted; disguised with paint, or with false show.
&Verbar;Fibulare: The bone or cartilage of the tarsus, which articulates with the fibula, and corresponds to the calcaneum in man and most mammals.
Frank: A member of one of the German tribes that in the fifth century overran and conquered Gaul, and established the kingdom of France.
Fibrinoplastin: An albuminous substance, existing in the blood, which in combination with fibrinogen forms fibrin; -- called also paraglobulin.
Fractural: Pertaining to, or consequent on, a fracture.
Fashionist: An obsequious follower of the modes and fashions.
fabricated: formed or conceived by the fancy or imagination; as, a fabricated excuse for his absence.
fulminate of mercury: The mercury salt of fulminic acid (Hg(CNO)2), called also mercury fulminate. It is prepared as gray crystals, and is used primarily in detonators for detonating high explosives, such as dynamite or TNT.
fingerpost: a guidepost resembling a hand with a pointing index finger.
face time: Time spent speaking with a person face-to-face; -- contrasted with time spent communicating by electronic media, such as telephone or e-mail, or via written communications; as, the chief of staff has the most face time with the president.
frogbit: A European plant (Hydrocharis Morsus-ranæ), floating on still water and propagating itself by runners. It has roundish heart-shaped leaves and small white flowers.
Flitch: To cut into, or off in, flitches or strips; as, to flitch logs; to flitch bacon.
Francophil: An admirer of France and everything French.
Fetich: A material object supposed among certain African tribes to represent in such a way, or to be so connected with, a supernatural being, that the possession of it gives to the possessor power to control that being.
Figary: A frolic; a vagary; a whim.
Freeborn: Born free; not born in vassalage; inheriting freedom.
flowered: resembling or made of or suggestive of flowers.
flat-top: having a flat or flattened upper surface.
Finality: The state of being final, finished, or complete; a final or conclusive arrangement; a settlement.
Federalist: An advocate of confederation; specifically (Amer. Hist.), a friend of the Constitution of the United States at its formation and adoption; a member of the political party which favored the administration of president Washington.
&Verbar;Fougade: A small mine, in the form of a well sunk from the surface of the ground, charged with explosive and projectiles. It is made in a position likely to be occupied by the enemy.
Freely: In a free manner; without restraint or compulsion; abundantly; gratuitously.
Fastener: One who, or that which, makes fast or firm.
Far-off: Remote; as, the far-off distance; troops landing on far-off shores.  Cf. Far-off, under Far, adv.
Ferry: A place where persons or things are carried across a river, arm of the sea, etc., in a ferryboat.
Fauna: The animals of any given area or epoch; as, the fauna of America; fossil fauna; recent fauna.
Floriform: Having the form of a flower; flower-shaped.
Frijol: In Mexico, the southwestern United States, and the West Indies, any cultivated bean of the genus Phaseolus, esp. the black seed of a variety of P. vulgaris.
fire-resistant: Not able to burn or able to burn only with difficulty.
Falsehood: Want of truth or accuracy; an untrue assertion or representation; error; misrepresentation; falsity.
Fairylike: Resembling a fairy, or what is made or done be fairies; as, fairylike music.
Froth: To throw up or out spume, foam, or bubbles; to foam; as beer froths; a horse froths.
Facility: The quality of being easily performed; freedom from difficulty; ease; as, the facility of an operation.
Fairing: A present; originally, one given or purchased at a fair.
Fiendish: Like a fiend; diabolically wicked or cruel; infernal; malignant; devilish; hellish.
Frote: To rub or wear by rubbing; to chafe.
Frank-law: The liberty of being sworn in courts, as a juror or witness; one of the ancient privileges of a freeman; free and common law; -- an obsolete expression signifying substantially the same as the American expression civil rights.
fingerpaint: A type of paint having the consistency of a thin paste or jelly, which is applied to a surface by dipping fingers into the paint and smearing the paint on the surface, usually in artistic patterns.  It is used primarily by children.
Feeder: One who, or that which, gives food or supplies nourishment; steward.
&Verbar;Ferrugo: A disease of plants caused by fungi, commonly called the rust, from its resemblance to iron rust in color.
Fidelity: Faithfulness; adherence to right; careful and exact observance of duty, or discharge of obligations.
Frizel: A movable furrowed piece of steel struck by the flint, to throw sparks into the pan, in an early form of flintlock.
Furcate: Forked; branching like a fork; as, furcate twigs.
Fibrine: Belonging to the fibers of plants.
Firestone: Iron pyrites, formerly used for striking fire; also, a flint.
Figpecker: The European garden warbler (Sylvia hortensis or Currica, hortensis); -- called also beccafico and greater pettychaps.
Fragmentist: A writer of fragments; as, the fragmentist of Wolfenbüttel.
Forsooth: A person who used forsooth much; a very ceremonious and deferential person.
Footing: Ground for the foot; place for the foot to rest on; firm foundation to stand on.
Firry: Made of fir; abounding in firs.
&Verbar;Fin de si\u00e8cle: Lit., end of the century; -- mostly used adjectively in English to signify: belonging to, or characteristic of, the close of the 19th century.  At that time the phrase was also intended to imply “modern” or “up-to-date;” as, fin-de-siècle ideas.
Fallopian: Pertaining to, or discovered by, Fallopius; as, the Fallopian tubes or oviducts, the ducts or canals which conduct the ova from the ovaries to the uterus.
Found: To lay the basis of; to set, or place, as on something solid, for support; to ground; to establish upon a basis, literal or figurative; to fix firmly.
Finding: That which is found, come upon, or provided; esp. (pl.), that which a journeyman artisan finds or provides for himself; as tools, trimmings, etc.
Frankalmoigne: A tenure by which a religious corporation holds lands given to them and their successors forever, usually on condition of praying for the soul of the donor and his heirs; -- called also tenure by free alms.
Flockmel: In a flock; in a body.
&Verbar;Fraxinus: A genus of deciduous forest trees, found in the north temperate zone, and including the true ash trees.
free-for-all: a noisy and disordered fight conducted without rules.
Fizz: A hissing sound; as, the fizz of a fly.
Fork: To raise, or pitch with a fork, as hay; to dig or turn over with a fork, as the soil.
Foredeem: To know or discover beforehand; to foretell.
Francic: Pertaining to the Franks, or their language; Frankish.
Fluviometer: An instrument for measuring the height of water in a river; a river gauge.
Fore: Before; -- sometimes written 'fore as if a contraction of afore or before.
Ford: To pass or cross, as a river or other water, by wading; to wade through.
Flimflam: A freak; a trick; a lie.
Ferret: The iron used for trying the melted glass to see if is fit to work, and for shaping the rings at the mouths of bottles.
Full-bottomed: Full and large at the bottom, as wigs worn by certain civil officers in Great Britain.
Frankish: Like, or pertaining to, the Franks.
filled: containing as much or as many as is possible or normal; as, filled to overflowing.  Opposite of empty.
Fort: A strong or fortified place; usually, a small fortified place, occupied only by troops, surrounded with a ditch, rampart, and parapet, or with palisades, stockades, or other means of defense; a fortification.
Forbear: To keep away from; to avoid; to abstain from; to give up; as, to forbear the use of a word of doubtful propriety.
Forever: Through eternity; through endless ages; eternally.
Free-soil: Pertaining to, or advocating, the non-extension of slavery; -- esp. applied to a party which was active during the period 1846-1856.
Fra: Brother; -- a title of a monk or friar; as, Fra Angelo.
Flyblown: Tainted or contaminated with flyblows; damaged; foul.
Fiddle: To play (a tune) on a fiddle.
Fathership: The state of being a father; fatherhood; paternity.
Fallacy: Deceptive or false appearance; deceitfulness; that which misleads the eye or the mind; deception.
Finnan haddie: Haddock cured in peat smoke, originally at Findon (pron. f&ibreve_;n"an), Scotland. the name is also applied to other kinds of smoked haddock.
Full-blown: Fully expanded, as a blossom; completely developed; as, a full-blown rose.
&Verbar;Falanaka: A viverrine mammal of Madagascar (Eupleres Goudotii), allied to the civet; -- called also Falanouc.
For-: A prefix to verbs, having usually the force of a negative or privative. It often implies also loss, detriment, or destruction, and sometimes it is intensive, meaning utterly, quite thoroughly, as in forbathe.
FHLMC: a corporation authorized by Congress to provide a secondary market for residential mortgages.  It is called Freddie Mac in the jargon of the finance industry.
Fecula: Any pulverulent matter obtained from plants by simply breaking down the texture, washing with water, and subsidence.
Fundamentally: Primarily; originally; essentially; radically; at the foundation; in origin or constituents.
Freeze: The act of congealing, or the state of being congealed.
Forfete: To incur a penalty; to transgress.
For: One who takes, or that which is said on, the affrimative side; that which is said in favor of some one or something; -- the antithesis of against, and commonly used in connection with it.
Filtrate: That which has been filtered; the liquid which has passed through the filter in the process of filtration.  Contrasted with retentate, the material remaining on the filter.
footlocker: a trunk for storing personal possessions; usually kept at the foot of a bed (as in a military barracks).
&Verbar;Fer\u00e6 natur\u00e6: Of a wild nature; -- applied to animals, as foxes, wild ducks, etc., in which no one can claim property.
Foredoom: Doom or sentence decreed in advance.
&Verbar;Fondus: A style of printing calico, paper hangings, etc., in which the colors are in bands and graduated into each other.
Felter: To clot or mat together like felt.
Free-martin: An imperfect female calf, twinborn with a male, which is sterile as a result of exposure to masculinizing hormones.
fluegelhorn: a brass instrument resembling a cornet but with a wider bore.
&Verbar;Felis: A genus of carnivorous mammals, including the domestic cat, the lion, tiger, panther, and similar animals.
&Verbar;Fondue: A dish made of cheese, eggs, butter, etc., often seasoned with kirsch and white wine, melted together, and usually used as a dip for pieces of bread.
Foreshadow: To shadow or typi&unr_;y beforehand; to prefigure.
Folly: The state of being foolish; want of good sense; levity, weakness, or derangement of mind.
Felt: To make into felt, or a feltike substance; to cause to adhere and mat together.
Filanders: A disease in hawks, characterized by the presence of small threadlike worms, also of filaments of coagulated blood, from the rupture of a vein; -- called also backworm.
frameshift: of, pertaining to, or causing a type of mutation consisting of the insertion or deletion of one or more nucleotides in the nucleic acid structure of a gene, when the number of base pairs inserted or deleted is not a multiple of three. If the addition or deletion occurs in multiples of three, the unaffected nucleotides in the genome remain in the proper order ("frame") to be correctly translated into protein; in such cases of insertions or deletions not causing a frame shift, a functional though altered protein may be produced by the organism.  Frameshift mutations cause more profound changes in the composition of the protein resulting from translation of the mutated gene.
Fell: A form of seam joining two pieces of cloth, the edges being folded together and the stitches taken through both thicknesses.
Fruticulose: Like, or pertaining to, a small shrub.
Forwaste: To desolate or lay waste utterly.
Fierce: Furious; violent; unrestrained; impetuous; as, a fierce wind.
&Verbar;Fahlband: A stratum in crystalline rock, containing metallic sulphides.
Futurition: The state of being future; futurity.
F: F is the sixth letter of the English alphabet, and a nonvocal consonant. Its form and sound are from the Latin. The Latin borrowed the form from the Greek digamma &unr_;, which probably had the value of English w consonant. The form and value of Greek letter came from the Phœnician, the ultimate source being probably Egyptian. Etymologically f is most closely related to p, k, v, and b; as in E. five, Gr. pe`nte; E. wolf, L. lupus, Gr. ly`kos; E. fox, vixen ; fragile, break; fruit, brook, v. t.; E. bear, L. ferre. See Guide to Pronunciation, §§ 178, 179, 188, 198, 230.
faineant: A do-nothing; an idle fellow; a sluggard.
Ferreous: Partaking of, made of, or pertaining to, iron; like iron.
Frondescence: The time at which each species of plants unfolds its leaves.
Fire beetle: A very brilliantly luminous beetle (Pyrophorus noctilucus), one of the elaters, found in Central and South America; -- called also cucujo.  The name is also applied to other species. See Firefly.
Foveolate: Having small pits or depressions, as the receptacle in some composite flowers.
Fester: A small sore which becomes inflamed and discharges corrupt matter; a pustule.
Filasse: Vegetable fiber, as jute or ramie, prepared for manufacture.
Family: The collective body of persons who live in one house, and under one head or manager; a household, including parents, children, and servants, and, as the case may be, lodgers or boarders.
Freakish: Apt to change the mind suddenly; whimsical; capricious.
Fibrillar: Of or pertaining to fibrils or fibers; as, fibrillar twitchings.
Ferm: Rent for a farm; a farm; also, an abode; a place of residence; as, he let his land to ferm.
Fern: An order of cryptogamous plants, the Filices, which have their fructification on the back of the fronds or leaves. They are usually found in humid soil, sometimes grow epiphytically on trees, and in tropical climates often attain a gigantic size.
Fire-new: Fresh from the forge; bright; quite new; brand-new.
Flat-footed: Having a flat foot, with little or no arch of the instep; suffering from fallen arches.
Fining: The act of imposing a fin&unr_;.
Fiduciary: One who holds a thing in trust for another; a trustee.
Fratricide: The act of one who murders or kills his own brother.
&Verbar;Froufrou: A rustling, esp. the rustling of a woman's dress.
Fibrillose: Covered with hairlike appendages, as the under surface of some lichens; also, composed of little strings or fibers; as, fibrillose appendages.
Furthersome: Tending to further, advance, or promote; helpful; advantageous.
Frustratory: Making void; rendering null; as, a frustratory appeal.
fundamentalism: A system of beliefs based on the interpretation of every word in the Bible, both old and new testaments, as literal truth.  It is primarily held by a branch of American Protestants.
&Verbar;Floride\u00e6: A subclass of algæ including all the red or purplish seaweeds; the Rhodospermeæ of many authors; -- so called from the rosy or florid color of most of the species.
Fumed oak: Oak given a weathered appearance by exposure in an air-tight compartment to fumes of ammonia from uncorked cans, being first given a coat of filler.
Furlough: To furnish with a furlough; to grant leave of absence to, as to an officer or soldier.
five-hitter: A game in which a pitcher allows the opposing team 5 hits.
Forelock: The lock of hair that grows from the forepart of the head.
&Verbar;Fer\u00e6: A group of mammals which formerly included the Carnivora, Insectivora, Marsupialia, and lemurs, but is now often restricted to the Carnivora.
Frieze: To make a nap on (cloth); to friz. See Friz, v. t., 2.
&Verbar;Forficula: A genus of insects including the earwigs. See Earwig, 1.
Friation: The act of breaking up or pulverizing.
Force: To use violence; to make violent effort; to strive; to endeavor.
Frog-eyed: Spotted with whitish specks due to a disease, or produced artificially by spraying; -- said of tobacco used for cigar wrappers.
Falcade: The action of a horse, when he throws himself on his haunches two or three times, bending himself, as it were, in very quick curvets.
Flotilla: A little fleet, or a fleet of small vessels.
Forfend: To prohibit; to forbid; to avert.
Forefather: One who precedes another in the line of genealogy in any degree, but usually in a remote degree; an ancestor.
fascist: of or pertaining to fascism; resembling fascism; as, fascist propaganda.
flannelcake: a flat cake of thin batter fried on both sides on a griddle; a pancake; a flapjack.
fascism: a political theory advocating an authoritarian hierarchical government; -- opposed to democracy and liberalism.
Furfuraceous: Made of bran; like bran; scurfy.
Fain: To be glad ; to wish or desire.
Fermeture: The mechanism for closing the breech of a breech-loading firearm, in artillery consisting principally of the breechblock, obturator, and carrier ring.
Federation: The act of uniting in a league; confederation.
Fury: Violent or extreme excitement; overmastering agitation or enthusiasm.
Fucusol: An oily liquid, resembling, and possibly identical with, furfurol, and obtained from fucus, and other seaweeds.
Foxfish: The fox shark; -- called also sea fox. See Thrasher shark, under Shark.
Forewot: pres. indic., 1st & 3d pers. sing. of Forewite.
Flexibility: The state or quality of being flexible; flexibleness; pliancy; pliability; as, the flexibility of strips of hemlock, hickory, whalebone or metal, or of rays of light.
flat-out: downright; plain; unqualified; as, a flat-out lie.
&Verbar;Fauces: The narrow passage from the mouth to the pharynx, situated between the soft palate and the base of the tongue; -- called also the isthmus of the fauces.  On either side of the passage two membranous folds, called the pillars of the fauces, inclose the tonsils.
furnished: provided with necessary furnishings; -- used especially of rented apartments having furniture included in the rental price; as, a furnished apartment.  Opposite of unfurnished.
Flatulent: Affected with flatus{2} or gases generated in the alimentary canal; windy.
Fitness: The state or quality of being fit; as, the fitness of measures or laws; a person's fitness for office.
Fossane: A species of civet (Viverra fossa) resembling the genet.
Florin: A silver coin of Florence, first struck in the twelfth century, and noted for its beauty. The name is given to different coins in different countries. The florin of England, first minted in 1849, is worth two shillings, or about 48 cents; the florin of the Netherlands, about 40 cents; of Austria, about 36 cents.
Fenny: Pertaining to, or inhabiting, a fen; abounding in fens; swampy; boggy.
Felonry: A body of felons; specifically, the convict population of a penal colony.
Fulvous: Tawny; dull yellow, with a mixture of gray and brown.
Finned: Having a fin, or fins, or anything resembling a fin.
funniness: a comic incident or series of incidents.
Flammability: The quality of being flammable; inflammability.
Frown: A wrinkling of the face in displeasure, rebuke, etc.; a sour, severe, or stern look; a scowl.
Flittermouse: A bat; -- called also flickermouse, flindermouse, and flintymouse.
Frache: A shallow iron pan to hold glass ware while being annealed.
&Verbar;Feringee: The name given to Europeans by the Hindos.
Forgetful: Apt to forget; easily losing remembrance; as, a forgetful man should use helps to strengthen his memory.
Freeze-dry: to remove the moisture from (e.g. food) by first freezing and then subjecting to a high vacuum; -- used as a mild method for drying foods or chemicals while causing little decomposition, in contrast to heat-drying.
First-hand: Obtained directly from the first or original source; hence, without the intervention of an agent; -- of information; as, a firsthand report; firsthand information; firsthand knowledge.
factual: of or pertaining to facts; as, factual inaccuracies.
Foliaceous: Belonging to, or having the texture or nature of, a leaf; having leaves intermixed with flowers; as, a foliaceous spike.
Fiants: The dung of the fox, wolf, boar, or badger.
Fortnightly: Occurring or appearing once in a fortnight; as, a fortnightly meeting of a club; a fortnightly magazine, or other publication.
&Verbar;Feria: A week day, esp. a day which is neither a festival nor a fast.
Fatherliness: The qualities of a father; parantal kindness, care, etc.
&Verbar;Fabella: One of the small sesamoid bones situated behind the condyles of the femur, in some mammals.
From: Out of the neighborhood of; lessening or losing proximity to; leaving behind; by reason of; out of; by aid of; -- used whenever departure, setting out, commencement of action, being, state, occurrence, etc., or procedure, emanation, absence, separation, etc., are to be expressed. It is construed with, and indicates, the point of space or time at which the action, state, etc., are regarded as setting out or beginning; also, less frequently, the source, the cause, the occasion, out of which anything proceeds; -- the antithesis and correlative of to; as, it, is one hundred miles from Boston to Springfield; he took his sword from his side; light proceeds from the sun; separate the coarse wool from the fine; men have all sprung from Adam, and often go from good to bad, and from bad to worse; the merit of an action depends on the principle from which it proceeds; men judge of facts from personal knowledge, or from testimony.
Fronto-: A combining form signifying relating to the forehead or the frontal bone; as, fronto-parietal, relating to the frontal and the parietal bones; fronto-nasal, etc.
Feudalism: The feudal system; a system by which the holding of estates in land is made dependent upon an obligation to render military service to the king or feudal superior; feudal principles and usages.
Fritfly: A small dipterous fly of the genus Oscinis, esp. O. vastator, injurious to grain in Europe, and O. Trifole, injurious to clover in America.
Filleting: The protecting of a joint, as between roof and parapet wall, with mortar, or cement, where flashing is employed in better work.
Fireball: A ball filled with powder or other combustibles, intended to be thrown among enemies, and to injure by explosion; also, to set fire to their works and light them up, so that movements may be seen.
Factorage: The allowance given to a factor, as a compensation for his services; -- called also a commission.
first-rate: of the highest quality; as, a first-rate reporter.
Fovilla: One of the fine granules contained in the protoplasm of a pollen grain.
Fibrin: A white, albuminous, fibrous substance, formed in the coagulation of the blood either by decomposition of fibrinogen, or from the union of fibrinogen and paraglobulin which exist separately in the blood. It is insoluble in water, but is readily digestible in gastric and pancreatic juice.
Fibril: A small fiber; the branch of a fiber; a very slender thread; a fibrilla.
Frank-fee: A species of tenure in fee simple, being the opposite of ancient demesne, or copyhold.
Formal: Belonging to the form, shape, frame, external appearance, or organization of a thing.
Forfeiture: The act of forfeiting; the loss of some right, privilege, estate, honor, office, or effects, by an offense, crime, breach of condition, or other act.
fuselage: The central, approximately cylindrical portion of an airplane which carries the passengers, crew, and cargo.  It usually forms the main structural portion of an airplane, and to it are typically attached the wings, tail, and sometimes the engines.  In single-propeller airplanes, the propeller is typically fixed at the front of the fuselage, although variants have been produced with the propeller at the rear.  Some airplanes have no fuselage, properly so called.
&Verbar;Frugivora: The fruit bate; a group of the Cheiroptera, comprising the bats which live on fruits. See Eruit bat, under Fruit.
Fructuary: One who enjoys the profits, income, or increase of anything.
formalwear: attire to wear on formal occasions in the evening.
Fleshling: A person devoted to fleshly things.
Falstaffian: of or pertaining to Falstaff, a character in Shakespeare's plays.
Falsely: In a false manner; erroneously; not truly; perfidiously or treacherously.
Fulgurating: Resembling lightning; -- used to describe intense lancinating pains accompanying locomotor ataxy.
Frogshell: One of numerous species of marine gastropod shells, belonging to Ranella and allied genera.
Filariidae: a natural family consisting of threadlike roundworms, called filariae.
Fetidness: The quality or state of being fetid.
Flight-shot: The distance to which an arrow or flight may be shot; bowshot, -- about the fifth of a mile.
flaccid: Yielding to pressure for want of firmness and stiffness; soft and weak; limber; lax; drooping; flabby; as, a flaccid muscle; flaccid flesh.
Funnel: A vessel of the shape of an inverted hollow cone, terminating below in a pipe, and used for conveying liquids or pourable solids into a vessel with a narrow opening; a tunnel.
Fitweed: A plant (Eryngium fœtidum) supposed to be a remedy for fits.
Featurely: Having features; showing marked peculiarities; handsome.
Faction: One of the divisions or parties of charioteers (distinguished by their colors) in the games of the circus.
Fez: A felt or cloth cap, usually red and having a tassel, -- a variety of the tarboosh. See Tarboosh.
Flusher: A workman employed in cleaning sewers by flushing them with water.
Freehold: An estate in real property, of inheritance (in fee simple or fee tail) or for life; or the tenure by which such estate is held.
&Verbar;Fondu: Blended; gradually changing or passing into each other by subtle gradations; -- said of colors or of the surface or material on which the colors are laid.
Fusel: A hot, acrid, oily liquid, accompanying many alcoholic liquors (as potato whisky, corn whisky, etc.), as an undesirable ingredient, and consisting of several of the higher alcohols and compound ethers, but mostly of amyl alcohol;
Formation: The act of giving form or shape to anything; a forming; a shaping.
&Verbar;Factum: A man's own act and deed
Flower State: Florida; -- a nickname, alluding to sense of L. floridus, from florida flowery. See Florid.
Fleaking: A light covering of reeds, over which the main covering is laid, in thatching houses.
Forisfamiliate: To renounce a legal title to a further share of paternal inheritance.
Foothold: A holding with the feet; firm standing; that on which one may tread or rest securely; footing.
Fragmentary: Composed of fragments, or broken pieces; disconnected; not complete or entire.
Filly: A female foal or colt; a young mare.  Cf. Colt, Foal.
Flawter: To scrape or pare, as a skin.
Fowlers solution: An aqueous solution of arsenite of potassium, of such strength that one hundred parts represent one part of arsenious acid, or white arsenic; -- named from Fowler, an English physician who first brought it into use.
Fettling: A mixture of ore, cinders, etc., used to line the hearth of a puddling furnace.
Faithed: Having faith or a faith; honest; sincere.
Further: To help forward; to promote; to advance; to forward; to help or assist.
follow-on: Following as a logical consequence or next step in a process; -- used mostly of voluntary actions.
Flooding: The filling or covering with water or other fluid; overflow; inundation; the filling anything to excess.
Fragrant: Affecting the olfactory nerves agreeably; sweet of smell; odorous; having or emitting an agreeable perfume.
Forasmuch: In consideration that; seeing that; since; because that; -- followed by as.  See under For, prep.
Footmanship: Art or skill of a footman.
Filature: A drawing out into threads; hence, the reeling of silk from cocoons.
Furnishment: The act of furnishing, or of supplying furniture; also, furniture.
Flower-de-luce: A genus of perennial herbs (Iris) with swordlike leaves and large three-petaled flowers often of very gay colors, but probably white in the plant first chosen for the royal French emblem.
Foreby: Near; hard by; along; past. See Forby.
Fated: Decreed by fate; destined; doomed; as, he was fated to rule a factious people.
Fancier: One who is governed by fancy.
Forehead: The front of that part of the head which incloses the brain; that part of the face above the eyes; the brow.
Fistic: Pertaining to boxing, or to encounters with the fists; puglistic; as, fistic exploits; fistic heroes.
Fenceless: Without a fence; uninclosed; open; unguarded; defenseless.
Fancied: Formed or conceived by the fancy; unreal; as, a fancied wrong.
Fractionate: To separate (a mixture of chemical substances) into different portions or fractions, as in the distillation of liquids.
Flange: To be bent into a flange.
Fratery: A frater house. See under Frater.
Flightiness: The state or quality of being flighty.
Furuncle: A superficial, inflammatory tumor, suppurating with a central core; a boil.
free-lance: to work on a free-lance basis; to work as a freelancer.
Fetlock: The cushionlike projection, bearing a tuft of long hair, on the back side of the leg above the hoof of the horse and similar animals. Also, the joint of the limb at this point (between the great pastern bone and the metacarpus), or the tuft of hair.
Firmness: The state or quality of being firm.
Fingerprint: an impression of the pattern of ridges on the skin of the last joint of a person's finger, left on a surface after a person has touched the surface.
Foreboding: Presage of coming ill; expectation of misfortune.
Fortuna: the goddess of fortune and good luck; counterpart of Greek Tyche.
featherbrained: Giddy; frivolous; lacking seriousness; given to frivolity; feather-headed.
Fistulous: Having the form or nature of a fistula; as, a fistulous ulcer.
Falcer: One of the mandibles of a spider.
Frequentative: Serving to express the frequent repetition of an action; as, a frequentative verb.
Favosite: Like or pertaining to the genus Favosites.
Fronted: Formed with a front; drawn up in line.
Fugue: A polyphonic composition, developed from a given theme or themes, according to strict contrapuntal rules. The theme is first given out by one voice or part, and then, while that pursues its way, it is repeated by another at the interval of a fifth or fourth, and so on, until all the parts have answered one by one, continuing their several melodies and interweaving them in one complex progressive whole, in which the theme is often lost and reappears.
Fyrd: The military force of the whole nation, consisting of all men able to bear arms.
Forequoted: Cited before; quoted in a foregoing part of the treatise or essay.
Fustigation: A punishment by beating with a stick or club; cudgeling.
Frey: The god of earth's fertility and peace and prosperity, presiding over rain, sunshine, and all the fruits of the earth, dispensing wealth among men; son of Njorth (Njord) and brother of Freya; originally of the Vanir; later with the Aesir.  He was especially worshipped in the temple at Upsala in Sweden
Fermentable: Capable of fermentation; as, cider and other vegetable liquors are fermentable.
Fives: A disease of the glands under the ear in horses; the vives.
Formulization: The act or process of reducing to a formula; the state of being formulized.
Fire-fanged: Injured as by fire; burned; -- said of manure which has lost its goodness and acquired an ashy hue in consequence of heat generated by decomposition.
Furnarius: The type genus of the Furnariidae, comprising the South American ovenbirds.
Falsifiable: Capable of being falsified, counterfeited, or corrupted.
&Verbar;Fungia: A genus of simple, stony corals; -- so called because they are usually flat and circular, with radiating plates, like the gills of a mushroom. Some of them are eighteen inches in diameter.
Fabaceae: a large family of trees, shrubs, vines, and herbs bearing bean pods; divided for convenience into the subfamilies Caesalpiniacea; Mimosaceae; Papilionaceae.
Flintware: A superior kind of earthenware into whose composition flint enters largely.
Flanched: Having flanches; -- said of an escutcheon with those bearings.
ftp: To send from one computer to another by means of the standard file transfer protocol (ftp); as, he ftp'd me the file yesterday.
Fraternal: Of, pertaining to, or involving, brethren; becoming to brothers; brotherly; as, fraternal affection; a fraternal embrace.
Flabellation: The act of keeping fractured limbs cool by the use of a fan or some other contrivance.
Floured: Finely granulated; -- said of quicksilver which has been granulated by agitation during the amalgamation process.
Freshmanship: The state of being a freshman.
Fraise: To protect, as a line of troops, against an onset of cavalry, by opposing bayonets raised obliquely forward.
Fraction: To separate by means of, or to subject to, fractional distillation or crystallization; to fractionate; -- frequently used with out; as, to fraction out a certain grade of oil from pretroleum.
Field: To catch, stop, throw, etc. (the ball), as a fielder.
&Verbar;Fioriture: Little flowers of ornament introduced into a melody by a singer or player.
folktale: a tale circulated by word of mouth among the common folk, especially one forming part of the tradition of a culture.
Footman: A soldier who marches and fights on foot; a foot soldier.
flatness: The quality or state of being flat.
Freighter: One who loads a ship, or one who charters and loads a ship.
&Verbar;Forsythia: A shrub of the Olive family, with yellow blossoms.
Ferine: Wild; untamed; savage; as, lions, tigers, wolves, and bears are ferine beasts.
Ferocious: Fierce; savage; wild; indicating cruelty; ravenous; rapacious; as, ferocious look or features; a ferocious lion.
Flighted: Taking flight; flying; -- used in composition.
Funeral: Pertaining to a funeral; used at the interment of the dead; as, funeral rites, honors, or ceremonies.
Forester: One who has charge of the growing timber on an estate; an officer appointed to watch a forest and preserve the game.
Famous: Celebrated in fame or public report; renowned; mach talked of; distinguished in story; -- used in either a good or a bad sense, chiefly the former; often followed by for; as, famous for erudition, for eloquence, for military skill; a famous pirate.
Faculty: Ability to act or perform, whether inborn or cultivated; capacity for any natural function; especially, an original mental power or capacity for any of the well-known classes of mental activity; psychical or soul capacity; capacity for any of the leading kinds of soul activity, as knowledge, feeling, volition; intellectual endowment or gift; power; as, faculties of the mind or the soul.
Foreadvise: To advise or counsel before the time of action, or before the event.
Francophone: Able to communicate in the French language; -- used especially of those whose native language is French.
fagging: Laborious drudgery; esp., the acting as a drudge for another at an English school.
Flutter: The act of fluttering; quick and irregular motion; vibration; as, the flutter of a fan.
Fatigate: To weary; to tire; to fatigue.
Free-swimming: Swimming in the open sea; -- said of certain marine animals.
Fluviatic: Belonging to rivers or streams; fluviatile.
Fluorescin: A colorless, amorphous substance which is produced by the reduction of fluoresceïn, and from which the latter may be formed by oxidation.
Fraying: The skin which a deer frays from his horns.
Fasciation: The act or manner of binding up; bandage; also, the condition of being fasciated.
fluoridize: to subject to fluoridation, as of water.
Filiation: The relationship of a son or child to a parent, esp. to a father.
Foreyard: The lowermost yard on the foremast.
Feebleness: The quality or condition of being feeble; debility; infirmity.
Farlie: An unusual or unexpected thing; a wonder. See Fearly.
Formicaroid: Like or pertaining to the family Formicaridæ or ant thrushes.
Fifty: The sum of five tens; fifty units or objects.
Fecal: Relating to, or containing, dregs, feces, or ordure; fæcal.
Fateful: Having the power of serving or accomplishing fate.
Furbelow: To put a furbelow on; to ornament.
Fabianism: the principles and beliefs of or similar to those of the Fabian Society, advocating socialism to be established by gradual reforms within the law.
First-class: Of the best class; of the highest rank; in the first division; of the best quality; first-rate; as, a first-class telescope.
functionalism: a psychology based on the assumption that all mental process are useful to an organism in adapting to the environment.
fascinated: having the attention fixed by a sense of wonder.
Fifth: The quotient of a unit divided by five; one of five equal parts; a fifth part.
Franklin: An English freeholder, or substantial householder.
&Verbar;Fl\u00fbte \u00e0 bec: A beak flute, an older form of the flute, played with a mouthpiece resembling a beak, and held like a flageolet.
Focalization: The act of focalizing or bringing to a focus, or the state of being focalized.
Feudality: The state or quality of being feudal; feudal form or constitution.
foaming: Giving off bubbles and developing a head of foam; as, a foaming glass of beer.
Fantigue: State of worry or excitment; fidget; ill humor.
far-reaching: having a wide range or effect; as, far-reaching (or extensive) forests; a far-reaching reform.
Fellowship: To acknowledge as of good standing, or in communion according to standards of faith and practice; to admit to Christian fellowship.
Fraunhofer lines: The lines of the spectrum; especially and properly, the dark lines of the solar spectrum, so called because first accurately observed and interpreted by Fraunhofer, a German physicist.
Fetish: See Fetich, n., Fetichism, n., Fetichistic, a.
Formosa: An island off the coast of China, also called Taiwan.  It was occupied by Japan from 1895 to 1945, when it was returned to Chinese sovereignty.  After the Communist revolution which took over the Chinese mainland in 1949, the Nationalist Chinese under Chang Kai-Shek retreated to the island of Formosa and established that island as the base of their government, being recognized for several years as the de jure possessor of the China seat in the United Nations.  The capital is Taipei.  As of 1998, both the Taiwan government and the mainland China government recognized Taiwan as properly a part of China, but the island is currently ruled as a de facto independent nation, though it does not possess a seat in the United Nations.  The question of when and under what circumstances the island will be reunited with the mainland government is still unresolved.
Fomalhaut: A star of the first magnitude, in the constellation Piscis Australis, or Southern Fish.
Forcible: Possessing force; characterized by force, efficiency, or energy; powerful; efficacious; impressive; influential.
Fumblingly: In the manner of one who fumbles.
fishing expedition: An investigation searching for evidence of wrongdoing, with no credible evidence of such wrongdoing available at the outset of the investigation, and often without specifying in advance the wrongdoing to be proven.
Filaria: a small, slender nematode worm of the family Onchocercidae (Filariidae) of many species, parasitic when adult in various animals, including man.  They may live within the blood, or in other bodily fluids, or within tissues or cavities of the body.  Infection with such organisms may be transmitted by blood-sucking arthropods.
Finnikin: A variety of pigeon, with a crest somewhat resembling the mane of a horse.
Fratercula: a genus of sea birds, one of the genera of puffins.
&Verbar;Farrago: A mass composed of various materials confusedly mixed; a medley; a mixture.
Funebrial: Pertaining to a funeral or funerals; funeral; funereal.
Flip-flap: With repeated strokes and noise, as of something long and loose.
Ferulaceous: Pertaining to reeds and canes; having a stalk like a reed; as, ferulaceous plants.
Flagelliform: Shaped like a whiplash; long, slender, round, flexible, and (comming) tapering.
&Verbar;Flaneur: One who strolls about aimlessly; a lounger; a loafer.
Foreskin: The fold of skin which covers the glans of the penis; the prepuce.
Frigate: Originally, a vessel of the Mediterranean propelled by sails and by oars. The French, about 1650, transferred the name to larger vessels, and by 1750 it had been appropriated for a class of war vessels intermediate between corvettes and ships of the line. Frigates, from about 1750 to 1850, had one full battery deck and, often, a spar deck with a lighter battery. They carried sometimes as many as fifty guns. After the application of steam to navigation steam frigates of largely increased size and power were built, and formed the main part of the navies of the world till about 1870, when the introduction of ironclads superseded them.
Fumacious: Smoky; hence, fond of smoking; addicted to smoking tobacco.
Fibrinous: Having, or partaking of the properties of, fibrin; as, fibrious exudation.
&Verbar;Fontange: A kind of tall headdress formerly worn.
Fighting: Qualified for war; fit for battle.
firedamp: a mixture of gases (mostly methane) that forms in coal mines and becomes explosive when mixed with air.  It is a source of serious hazard in coal mining operations.
Festoony: Pertaining to, consisting of, or resembling, festoons.
factotum: A person employed to do all kinds of work or business; a person with many different responsibilities.
Feeble-minded: Weak in intellectual power; wanting firmness or constancy; irresolute; vacillating; imbecile.
firstborn: The first child born to a parent; as, his firstborn was showered with gifts from relatives.
Fungibles: Things which may be furnished or restored in kind, as distinguished from specific things; -- called also fungible things.
Falseness: The state of being false; contrariety to the fact; inaccuracy; want of integrity or uprightness; double dealing; unfaithfulness; treachery; perfidy; as, the falseness of a report, a drawing, or a singer's notes; the falseness of a man, or of his word.
Freshman: A novice; one in the rudiments of knowledge; especially, a student during his first year in a high school, college, or university.
Furbish: To rub or scour to brightness; to clean; to burnish; as, to furbish a sword or spear.
Frogmouth: One of several species of Asiatic and East Indian birds of the genus Batrachostomus  (family Podargidæ); -- so called from their very broad, flat bills.
Florentine: A native or inhabitant of Florence, a city in Italy.
Feldspar: A name given to a group of minerals, closely related in crystalline form, and all silicates of alumina with either potash, soda, lime, or, in one case, baryta.
