They occur in crystals and crystalline masses, vitreous in luster, and breaking rather easily in two directions at right angles to each other, or nearly so. The colors are usually white or nearly white, flesh-red, bluish, or greenish.
Froise: A kind of pancake. See 1st Fraise.
Foredesign: To plan beforehand; to intend previously.
Ferranti phenomenon: An increase in the ratio of transformation of an alternating current converter, accompanied by other changes in electrical conditions, occurring when the secondary of the converter is connected with a condenser of moderate capacity; -- so called because first observed in connection with the Ferranti cables in London.
fraxin: A colorless crystalline substance (C16H18O10) found in the bark of the ash (Fraxinus), and along with esculin in the bark of the horse-chestnut.  It is structurally a derivative of a coumarin glucoside. It shows a delicate blue-green fluorescence in alkaline solutions; -- called also paviin and fraxoside.
Fungous: Of the nature of fungi; spongy.
Funding: Providing a fund for the payment of the interest or principal of a debt.
Fireflaire: A European sting ray of the genus Trygon (T. pastinaca); -- called also fireflare and fiery flaw.
Felidae: a natural family of lithe-bodied round-headed fissiped mammals, including the cats; wildcats; lions; leopards; cheetahs; and saber-toothed tigers.
&Verbar;Frisure: The dressing of the hair by crisping or curling.
Foot Guards: Infantry soldiers belonging to select regiments called the Guards.
Frost signal: A signal consisting of a white flag with a black center, used by the United States Weather Bureau to indicate that a local frost is expected. It is used only in Florida and along the coasts of the Pacific and the Gulf Mexico.
Francolin: A spurred partidge of the genus Francolinus and allied genera, of Asia and Africa. The common species (F. vulgaris) was formerly common in southern Europe, but is now nearly restricted to Asia.
flameproof: not susceptible to burning; noncombustible; fireproof; -- of artifacts.  Opposite of combustible.
Fresh-water: Of, pertaining to, or living in, water which is not salty; as, fresh-water geological deposits; a fresh-water fish; fresh-water mussels.
Ferment: To undergo fermentation; to be in motion, or to be excited into sensible internal motion, as the constituent particles of an animal or vegetable fluid; to work; to effervesce.
fire sale: a sale of objects damaged by fire, usually at much reduced prices.
&Verbar;Fiord: A narrow inlet of the sea, penetrating between high banks or rocks, as on the coasts of Norway and Alaska.
Fugh: An exclamation of disgust; foh; faugh.
Federal National Mortgage Association: A federally chartered corporation that purchases and resells mortgages.
Fellowlike: Like a companion; companionable; on equal terms; sympathetic.
Finicking: Finical; unduly particular; excessively demanding over minor details.
free-base: To ingest the basic form of a narcotic drug, usually by injection.
Favored: Countenanced; aided; regarded with kindness; as, a favored friend.
&Verbar;Frimaire: The third month of the French republican calendar. It commenced November 21, and ended December 20., See Vendémiaire.
Fastidious: Difficult to please; delicate to a fault; suited with difficulty; squeamish; as, a fastidious mind or ear; a fastidious appetite.
Faintly: In a faint, weak, or timidmanner.
Flutemouth: A fish of the genus Aulostoma, having a much elongated tubular snout.
Frolic: To play wild pranks; to play tricks of levity, mirth, and gayety; to indulge in frolicsome play; to sport.
fierceness: the quality of being fierce; ferocity; fury; vehemence.
Firer: One who fires or sets fire to anything; an incendiary.
Frenzy: To affect with frenzy; to drive to madness
Facial: Of or pertaining to the face; as, the facial artery, vein, or nerve.
Felicitate: To make very happy; to delight.
Flowering: The act of blossoming, or the season when plants blossom; florification.
Favorer: One who favors; one who regards with kindness or friendship; a well-wisher; one who assists or promotes success or prosperity.
Favier explosive: Any of several explosive mixtures, chiefly of ammonium nitrate and a nitrate derivative of naphthalene.  They are stable, but require protection from moisture.  As prepared it is a compressed cylinder of the explosive, filled with loose powder of the same composition, all inclosed in waterproof wrappers.  It is used for mining.
Forcipate: Like a pair of forceps; as, a forcipated mouth.
flatfoot: a police officer, especially a foot patrolman.
Fellow-commoner: A student at Cambridge University, England, who commons, or dines, at the Fellow's table.
Fictional: Pertaining to, or characterized by, fiction; fictitious; romantic.
free-range: permitted to graze or forage rather than being confined to a feedlot; -- of livestock and domestic poultry.
Frumentation: A largess of grain bestowed upon the people, to quiet them when uneasy.
fiberboard: a type of wallboard composed of wood chips or shavings bonded together with resin and compressed into rigid sheets, calle also particle board.
Formication: A sensation resembling that made by the creeping of ants on the skin.
Felwort: A European herb (Swertia perennis) of the Gentian family.
Footbath: A bath for the feet; also, a vessel used in bathing the feet.
Forcite: A gelatin dynamite in which the dope is composed largely of sodium nitrate.
Firearm: A gun, pistol, or any weapon from which a shot is discharged by the force of an explosive substance, as gunpowder.
Flying boat: A compact form of hydro-aëroplane having one central body, or hull.
flavorless: Without flavor; tasteless.  Opposite of flavorful.
Formulary: A book containing stated and prescribed forms, as of oaths, declarations, prayers, medical formulaæ, etc.; a book of precedents.
Fish-bellied: Bellying or swelling out on the under side; as, a fish-bellied rail.
Fulmar: One of several species of sea birds, of the family Procellariidæ, allied to the albatrosses and petrels. Among the well-known species are the arctic fulmar (Fulmarus glacialis) (called also fulmar petrel, malduck, and mollemock), and the giant fulmar (Ossifraga gigantea).
Fabulize: To invent, compose, or relate fables or fictions.
Firecrest: A small European kinglet (Regulus ignicapillus), having a bright red crest; -- called also fire-crested wren.
Freemasonic: Pertaining to, or resembling, the institutions or the practices of freemasons; as, a freemasonic signal.
Fecial: Pertaining to heralds, declarations of war, and treaties of peace; as, fecial law.
fifth column: a group of persons inside the battle lines of a territory engaged in a conflict, who secretly sympathize with the enemy, and who engage in espionage or sabotage; -- sometimes also referred to as a trojan horse.
free-enterprise: Of or pertaining to the free enterprise system having private ownership of the means of production and competition between enterprises.
Friz: That which is frizzed; anything crisped or curled, as a wig; a frizzle.
Frush: The frog of a horse's foot.
Franciscan: A monk or friar of the Order of St. Francis, a large and zealous order of mendicant monks founded in 1209 by St. Francis of Assisi. They are called also Friars Minor; and in England, Gray Friars, because they wear a gray habit.
Farinaceous: Consisting or made of meal or flour; as, a farinaceous diet.
Fracas: An uproar; a noisy quarrel; a disturbance; a brawl.
Friabiiity: The quality of being friable; friableness.
Fluavil: A hydrocarbon extracted from gutta-percha, as a yellow, resinous substance; -- called also fluanil.
funeral home: An establishment, usually commercial, where the bodies of dead persons are prepared for viewing before burial or cremation; called also funeral parlor, mortuary, funeral chapel and informally, undertaker's.  The body may or may not be preserved by embalming before viewing or burial, and in some cases the body is not exposed for viewing, though present in a casket.  Often, some form of memorial service is held for the deceased at the funeral home, where friends and relatives may come to pay their respects to the dead, and express condolence to the family.  The work of preparation of the body and many other arrangements related to the funeral and burial are carried out by an undertaker or mortician who manages the funeral home.
fucked-up: snarled or stalled in complete confusion.
Fiber optics: that branch of optics which studies the transmission of light through thin transparent fibers.
Forejudge: To expel from court for some offense or misconduct, as an attorney or officer; to deprive or put out of a thing by the judgment of a court.
Furring: The leveling of a surface, or the preparing of an air space, by means of strips of board or of larger pieces. See Fur, v. t., 3.
Filariasis: the presence of filariae within the body of an organism; infection with filariae. It is mostly found in tropical and subtropical regions.
Formidableness: The quality of being formidable, or adapted to excite dread.
Fleshy: Full of, or composed of, flesh; plump; corpulent; fat; gross.
Foresail: The sail bent to the foreyard of a square-rigged vessel, being the lowest sail on the foremast.
Forestick: Front stick of a hearth fire.
Freethinker: One who speculates or forms opinions independently of the authority of others; esp., in the sphere or religion, one who forms opinions independently of the authority of revelation or of the church; an unbeliever; -- a term assumed by deists and skeptics in the eighteenth century.
Furbisher: One who furbishes; esp., a sword cutler, who finishes sword blades and similar weapons.
Flick: A light quick stroke or blow, esp. with something pliant; a flirt; also, the sound made by such a blow.
Frondlet: A very small frond, or distinct portion of a compound frond.
Full-manned: Completely furnished wiith men, as a ship.
Fence: To make a defense; to guard one's self of anything, as against an attack; to give protection or security, as by a fence.
Footcloth: Formerly, a housing or caparison for a horse.
Fixture: That which is fixed or attached to something as a permanent appendage; as, the fixtures of a pump; the fixtures of a farm or of a dwelling, that is, the articles which a tenant may not take away.
flamefish: a bright red perchlike fish (Apogon maculatus) found in tropical Atlantic coastal waters.
&Verbar;Falx: A curved fold or process of the dura mater or the peritoneum; esp., one of the partitionlike folds of the dura mater which extend into the great fissures of the brain.
Fend: To act on the defensive, or in opposition; to resist; to parry; to shift off.
Flowerer: A plant which flowers or blossoms.
Frothy: Full of foam or froth, or consisting of froth or light bubbles; spumous; foamy.
Flushness: The state of being flush; abundance.
fiddle-shaped: shaped like a fiddle; -- of a leaf shape.
farmerette: a woman working on a farm; a farmeress.
femoris: The thigh bone; same as femur.
Flexible: Capable of being flexed or bent; admitting of being turned, bowed, or twisted, without breaking; pliable; yielding to pressure; not stiff or brittle.
&Verbar;Feu de joie: A fire kindled in a public place in token of joy; a bonfire; a firing of guns in token of joy.
Fleshment: The act of fleshing, or the excitement attending a successful beginning.
Floriation: Ornamentation by means of flower forms, whether closely imitated or conventionalized.
Fossilization: The process of converting, or of being converted, into a fossil.
Footworn: Worn by, or weared in, the feet; as, a footworn path; a footworn traveler.
&Verbar;Frontignac: A sweet muscadine wine made in Frontignan (Languedoc), France.
Freckly: Full of or marked with freckles; sprinkled with spots; freckled.
Falconer: A person who breeds or trains hawks for taking birds or game; one who follows the sport of fowling with hawks.
Falconet: One of the smaller cannon used in the 15th century and later.
Fulmarus: A genus of birds including many of the fulmars.
Fungin: A name formerly given to cellulose found in certain fungi and mushrooms.
Fustic: The wood of the Maclura tinctoria, a tree growing in the West Indies, used in dyeing yellow; -- called also old fustic.
Foregift: A premium paid by a lessee when taking his lease.
Flamboyant: Characterized by waving or flamelike curves, as in the tracery of windows, etc.; -- said of the later (15th century) French Gothic style.
Fuscin: A brown, nitrogenous pigment contained in the retinal epithelium; a variety of melanin.
&Verbar;Fascia: A band, sash, or fillet; especially, in surgery, a bandage or roller.
Fuller: To form a groove or channel in, by a fuller or set hammer; as, to fuller a bayonet.
first-come-first-served: distributed in order to those who request it in person; not subject to reservation for later delivery.  Contrasted with reservable.
foghorn: A horn that emits a loud low-pitched sound, used on ships navigating in a fog, to warn other ships of their presence.
Flat-headed: Having a head with a flattened top; as, a flat-headed nail.
Fertile: Producing fruit or vegetation in abundance; fruitful; able to produce abundantly; prolific; fecund; productive; rich; inventive; as, fertile land or fields; a fertile mind or imagination.
Fatuity: Weakness or imbecility of mind; stupidity.
Fumifugist: One who, or that which, drives away smoke or fumes.
Frankpledge: A pledge or surety for the good behavior of freemen, -- each freeman who was a member of an ancient decennary, tithing, or friborg, in England, being a pledge for the good conduct of the others, for the preservation of the public peace; a free surety.
fledged: having developed feathers or plumage; often used in combination; -- of birds.
Frequence: A crowd; a throng; a concourse.
Flap: To move as do wings, or as something broad or loose; to fly with wings beating the air.
Florist: A cultivator of, or dealer in, flowers.
Foretoken: To foreshow; to presignify; to prognosticate.
flugelhorn: a brass wind instrument resembling a cornet but with a wider bore, and having three valves.
Ferocactus: a genus of nearly globular cacti of Mexico and Southwestern U. S., including some of the barrel cacti.
Forebrain: The anterior of the three principal divisions of the brain, including the prosencephalon and thalamencephalon. Sometimes restricted to the prosencephalon only. See Brain.
Foreknowledge: Knowledge of a thing before it happens, or of whatever is to happen; prescience.
Fatidical: Having power to foretell future events; prophetic; fatiloquent; as, the fatidical oak.
Fleshly: In a fleshly manner; carnally; lasciviously.
Fodder: To feed, as cattle, with dry food or cut grass, etc.; to furnish with hay, straw, oats, etc.
forward-looking: planning for the future; concerned primarily with the future; -- contrasted with conern for the immediate present or reacting to past events.
&Verbar;Foyer: A lobby in a theater; a greenroom.
&Verbar;Furculum: The wishbone or merrythought of birds, formed by the united clavicles.
Fountain: A spring of water issuing from the earth.
Frugal: Economical in the use or appropriation of resources; not wasteful or lavish; wise in the expenditure or application of force, materials, time, etc.; characterized by frugality; sparing; economical; saving; as, a frugal housekeeper; frugal of time.
fox trot: a ballroom dance for couples in quadruple time, combining short and long and fast and slow steps in fixed sequences.
Fully: In a full manner or degree; completely; entirely; without lack or defect; adequately; satisfactorily; as, to be fully persuaded of the truth of a proposition.
&Verbar;Fragor: A loud and sudden sound; the report of anything bursting; a crash.
Frontless: Without face or front; shameless; not diffident; impudent.
Flatfish: Any fish of the family Pleuronectidæ; esp., the winter flounder (Pleuronectes Americanus). The flatfishes have the body flattened, swim on the side, and have eyes on one side, as the flounder, turbot, and halibut. See Flounder.
Fomenter: One who foments; one who encourages or instigates; as, a fomenter of sedition.
Feather-edge: The thin, new growth around the edge of a shell, of an oyster.
Frugivorous: Feeding on fruit, as birds and other animals.
Familiary: Of or pertaining to a family or household; domestic.
Footlicker: A sycophant; a fawner; a toady.  Cf. Bootlick.
Flawy: Full of flaws or cracks; broken; defective; faulty.
Featherstitch: A kind of embroidery stitch producing a branching zigzag line.
fantail goldfish: a type of goldfish bred artificially, having a realtively short oval body and a tail with four lobes arrayed somewhat like a folding fan, as though forming a part of the surface of a cone.  Called also fantail.
Flitter: A rag; a tatter; a small piece or fragment.
Fetter: To put fetters upon; to shackle or confine the feet of with a chain; to bind.
Fettered: Seeming as if fettered, as the feet of certain animals which bend backward, and appear unfit for walking.
Forslugge: To lsoe by idleness or slotch.
Friary: A monastery; a convent of friars.
Finally: At the end or conclusion; ultimately; lastly; as, the contest was long, but the Romans finally conquered.
full-scale: using all available resources; -- of actions; as, a full-scale effort to find the perpetrator.
four-in-hand: A long necktie that is tied in a slipknot with one end hanging in front of the other.
Fineness: The quality or condition of being fine.
Fretten: Rubbed; marked; as, pock-fretten, marked with the smallpox.
-ful: A suffix signifying full of, abounding with; as, boastful, harmful, woeful.
Fortunateness: The condition or quality of being fortunate; good luck; success; happiness.
Forlore: imp. pl. & p. p. of Forlese.
Foot ton: A unit of energy or work, being equal to the work done in raising one ton against the force of gravity through the height of one foot.
Fautor: A favorer; a patron; one who gives countenance or support; an abettor.
Fibrinogen: An albuminous substance existing in the blood, and in other animal fluids, which either alone or with fibrinoplastin or paraglobulin forms fibrin, and thus causes coagulation.
Foreigner: A person belonging to or owning allegiance to a foreign country; one not native in the country or jurisdiction under consideration, or not naturalized there; an alien; a stranger.
flyswat: An implement with a flat part (a mesh of metal or plastic) and a long handle, used to kill insects by striking them.  The handle is typically about one foot long and the flat mesh at the end (usually of plastic) is about 5 inces square.
Freshly: In a fresh manner; vigorously; newly, recently; brightly; briskly; coolly; as, freshly gathered; freshly painted; the wind blows freshly.
Flawn: A sort of flat custard or pie.
finger cot: a close-fitting sheath worn at the end of a finger, for protection of the finger or to avoid soiling the object touched.
Firth: An arm of the sea; a frith.
Full-sailed: Having all its sails set,; hence, without restriction or reservation.
Fiber: One of the delicate, threadlike portions of which the tissues of plants and animals are in part constituted; as, the fiber of flax or of muscle.
Foggy: Filled or abounding with fog, or watery exhalations; misty; as, a foggy atmosphere; a foggy morning.
Fribble: To act in a trifling or foolish manner; to act frivolously.
&Verbar;Filaria: a former genus comprised of certain nematodes, now classed as belonging to several genera within the family Onchocercidae.   See Onchocerca and Guinea worm.
Far-about: A going out of the way; a digression.
Future: That is to be or come hereafter; that will exist at any time after the present; as, the next moment is future, to the present.
Figuration: The act of giving figure or determinate form; determination to a certain form.
&Verbar;Funis: A cord; specifically, the umbilical cord or navel string.
Feoffee: The person to whom a feoffment is made; the person enfeoffed.
Fadge: A small flat loaf or thick cake; also, a fagot.
Fabricator: One who fabricates; one who constructs or makes.
Foresignify: To signify beforehand; to foreshow; to typify.
fine-tune: to adjust carefully and precisely so as to achieve optimum performance or efficiency; as, The mechanic fine-tuned the engine.
Fanfoot: A species of gecko having the toes expanded into large lobes for adhesion. The Egyptian fanfoot (Phyodactylus gecko) is believed, by the natives, to have venomous toes.
Figurate: Of a definite form or figure.
Fidalgo: The lowest title of nobility in Portugal, corresponding to that of Hidalgo in Spain.
&Verbar;Faubourg: A suburb of a French city; also, a district now within a city, but formerly without its walls.
Floutingly: With flouting; insultingly; as, to treat a lover floutingly.
Fallowness: A well or opening, through the successive floors of a warehouse or manufactory, through which goods are raised or lowered.
fishtail: to have the rear end skid from side to side, out of control: -- said of automobiles or other vehicles.
&Verbar;Felo-de-se: One who deliberately puts an end to his own existence, or loses his life while engaged in the commission of an unlawful or malicious act; a suicide.
Freight: To load with goods, as a ship, or vehicle of any kind, for transporting them from one place to another; to furnish with freight; as, to freight a ship; to freight a car.
Friable: Easily crumbled, pulverized, or reduced to powder.
fine-tooth: having fine teeth set close together; as, a fine-tooth comb.
Forty-niner: One the miners who took part in the California gold rush in 1849; an argonaut.
Fusarole: A molding generally placed under the echinus or quarter round of capitals in the Doric, Ionic, and Corinthian orders of architecture.
flawed: having flaws or imperfections; not perfect; -- applied broadly; as, a flawed vase; a flawed performance; a flawed character.
&Verbar;Fraise: A defense consisting of pointed stakes driven into the ramparts in a horizontal or inclined position.
Flavine: A yellow, crystalline, organic base, C13H12N2O, obtained artificially.
&Verbar;Funiculus: A cord, baud, or bundle of fibers; esp., one of the small bundles of fibers, of which large nerves are made up; applied also to different bands of white matter in the brain and spinal cord.
Finlet: A little fin; one of the parts of a divided fin.
Faradize: To stimulate with, or subject to, faradic, or inducted, electric currents.
Flatboat: A boat with a flat bottom and square ends; -- used for the transportation of bulky freight, especially in shallow waters.
Fumigator: One who, or that which, fumigates; an apparattus for fumigating.
Four-way stop: An intersection of two roads having stop signs at all four entry points.  The usual rule for such intersections requires that those entering the intersection yield the right of way to vehicles entering before them.
feudal: Of or pertaining to feuds, fiefs, or fees; as, feudal rights or services; feudal tenures.
Foxglove: Any plant of the genus Digitalis. The common English foxglove (Digitalis purpurea) is a handsome perennial or biennial plant, whose leaves are used as a powerful medicine, both as a sedative and diuretic. See Digitalis.
Fireweed: An American plant (Erechthites hiercifolia), very troublesome in spots where brushwood has been burned.
Fortunella: small genus of shrubs called kumquats, native to South China, producing small ovoid orangelike fruits called kumquats.
Fashion-monger: One who studies the fashions; a fop; a dandy.
Foolhardiness: Courage without sense or judgment; foolish rashness; recklessness.
Foal: To bring forth young, as an animal of the horse kind.
Foam: To cause to foam; as, to foam the goblet; also (with out), to throw out with rage or violence, as foam.
Fleeced: Furnished with a fleece; as, a sheep is well fleeced.
Forwander: To wander away; to go astray; to wander far and to weariness.
Fixedness: The state or quality of being fixed; stability; steadfastness.
Finnic: Of or pertaining to the Finns.
Flagellation: A beating or flogging; a whipping; a scourging.
Fulahs: A peculiar African race of uncertain origin, but distinct from the negro tribes, inhabiting an extensive region of Western Soudan. Their color is brown or yellowish bronze. They are Mohammedans. Called also Fellatahs, Foulahs, and Fellani. Fulah and Fulani are also used adjectively; as, Fulah or Fulani empire, tribes, language.
Fleecer: One who fleeces or strips unjustly, especially by trickery or fraund.
Forthink: To repent; to regret; to be sorry for; to cause regret.
-ferous: A suffix signifying bearing, producing, yielding; as, auriferous, yielding gold; chyliferous, producing chyle.
fastball: a baseball thrown with maximum velocity.
Firstborn: First brought forth; first in the order of birth; eldest; hence, most excellent; most distinguished or exalted; as, the firstborn child.
F\u00eang-shui: A system of spirit influences for good and evil believed by the Chinese to attend the natural features of landscape; also, a kind of geomancy dealing with these influences, used in determining sites for graves, houses, etc.
Fitter: A little piece; a flitter; a flinder.
Freud: Sigmund Freud, the founder of the practise of psychoanalysis.  Born 1856, died 1939.
Fascicular: Pertaining to a fascicle; fascicled; as, a fascicular root.
&Verbar;Fratricelli: The name which St. Francis of Assisi gave to his followers, early in the 13th century.
Fission: A cleaving, splitting, or breaking up into parts.
Flavorous: Imparting flavor; pleasant to the taste or smell; sapid.
&Verbar;Flota: A fleet; especially, a &unr_;eet of Spanish ships which formerly sailed every year from Cadiz to Vera Cruz, in Mexico, to transport to Spain the production of Spanish America.
&Verbar;F\u00e6ces: Excrement; ordure; also, settlings; sediment after infusion or distillation.
Frigidity: The condition or quality of being frigid; coldness; want of warmth.
-footer: a suffix designating something with a length of (so many) feet; -- used only in combinations with a numerical prefix; as, he is a six-footer; the golfer sank a 40-footer; his yacht is a 60-footer.
Felicitous: Characterized by felicity; happy; prosperous; delightful; skillful; successful; happily applied or expressed; appropriate.
full-term: Gestated for the entire duration of normal pregnancy; as, a healthy full-term baby; -- of new-born infants.  Opposite of premature.
Freer: One who frees, or sets free.
Fullness: The state of being full, or of abounding; abundance; completeness.
Flag: To lay with flags of flat stones.
Foxed: Discolored or stained; -- said of timber, and also of the paper of books or engravings.
force-feed: a method of lubricating internal combustion engines in which a pump forces oil into the engine bearings.
Fastness: The state of being fast and firm; firmness; fixedness; security; faithfulness.
Fricace: Meat sliced and dressed with strong sauce.
Farmery: The buildings and yards necessary for the business of a farm; a homestead.
Fermentative: Causing, or having power to cause, fermentation; produced by fermentation; fermenting; as, a fermentative process.
fallaciousness: result of a fallacy or error in reasoning.
firebug: a criminal who illegaly sets fire to property; an arsonist.
follow-up: a second (or subsequent) action to increase the effectiveness of an initial action.  Also used attributively; as a follow-up visit.
felid: any of various lithe-bodied round-headed fissiped mammals, many with retractile claws; a member of the Felidae.
Footstool: A low stool to support the feet of one when sitting.
fifty-fifty: a lottery in which the organizers retain fifty percent of the money wagered, and distribute fifty percent of the wagered money to the winner.
Flintwood: An Australian name for the very hard wood of the Eucalyptus piluralis.
Full-winged: Having large and strong or complete wings.
&Verbar;Fabliau: One of the metrical tales of the Trouvères, or early poets of the north of France.
Furzy: Abounding in, or overgrown with, furze; characterized by furze.
Famously: In a famous manner; in a distinguished degree; greatly; splendidly.
Foregut: The anterior part of the alimentary canal, from the mouth to the intestine, or to the entrance of the bile duct.
Flatulence: The state or quality of being flatulent.
Foliar: Consisting of, or pertaining to, leaves; as, foliar appendages.
friars-cowl: A tuberous perennial (Arisarum vulgare) having a cowl-shaped maroon or violet-black spathe; -- found in the Mediterranean, Canaries, and Azores.
Formaldehyde: A colorless, volatile liquid, H2CO, resembling acetic or ethyl aldehyde, and chemically intermediate between methyl alcohol and formic acid.
Fluty: Soft and clear in tone, like a flute.
Fyke: A long bag net distended by hoops, into which fish can pass easily, without being able to return; -- called also fyke net.
Frontage: The front part of an edifice or lot; extent of front.
Flat: To become flat, or flattened; to sink or fall to an even surface.
Flash point: the lowest temperature at which the vapors given off by a volatile liquid exposed to air will burst into flame when approached by a flame.  Also called flashing point.
Foundry: The act, process, or art of casting metals.
Faunist: One who describes the fauna of country; a naturalist.
Fucus: A paint; a dye; also, false show.
fortuneteller: a person who claims to be able to foretell events in the future of another person.
Flagginess: The condition of being flaggy; laxity; limberness.
&Verbar;Fourneau: The chamber of a mine in which the powder is placed.
Face: To carry a false appearance; to play the hypocrite.
Florification: The act, process, or time of flowering; florescence.
Faints: The impure spirit which comes over first and last in the distillation of whisky; -- the former being called the strong faints, and the latter, which is much more abundant, the weak faints. This crude spirit is much impregnated with fusel oil.
Forestaff: An instrument formerly used at sea for taking the altitudes of heavenly bodies, now superseded by the sextant; -- called also cross-staff.
Flunkydom: The place or region of flunkies.
Functionally: In a functional manner; as regards normal or appropriate activity.
Fancy: Adapted to please the fancy or taste, especially when of high quality or unusually appealing; ornamental; as, fancy goods; fancy clothes.
Franklinic: Of or pertaining to Benjamin Franklin.
&Verbar;Fungi Imperfecti: A heterogenous phylum of fungi which lack a sexual phase, or of which the sexual phase is not known. Some undoubtedly represent the conidium stages of various Ascomycetes. It is not considered a natural phylum, and is also called the Deuteromycota.  The group is divided into the orders Sphæropsidales, Melanconiales, and Moniliales.  It includes the genera Penicillium and Aspergillus, which reproduce asexually by means of conidia.
free-reed: a reed that does not fit closely over the aperture.
Flounce: To deck with a flounce or flounces; as, to flounce a petticoat or a frock.
Fir: A genus (Abies) of coniferous trees, often of large size and elegant shape, some of them valued for their timber and others for their resin. The species are distinguished as the balsam fir, the silver fir, the red fir, etc.  The Scotch fir is a Pinus.
Fissure: To cleave; to divide; to crack or fracture.
Fatherless: Destitute of a living father; as, a fatherless child.
Fix: A position of difficulty or embarassment; predicament; dilemma.
Faint: To cause to faint or become dispirited; to depress; to weaken.
Forktail: One of several Asiatic and East Indian passerine birds, belonging to Enucurus, and allied genera. The tail is deeply forked.
Fid: A square bar of wood or iron, used to support the topmast, being passed through a hole or mortise at its heel, and resting on the trestle trees.
Fie: An exclamation denoting contempt or dislike. See Fy.
Fudge wheel: A tool for ornamenting the edge of a sole.
Forehook: A piece of timber placed across the stem, to unite the bows and strengthen the fore part of the ship; a breast hook.
Fin: An organ of a fish, consisting of a membrane supported by rays, or little bony or cartilaginous ossicles, and serving to balance and propel it in the water.
Fil: imp. of Fall, v. i. Fell.
funerary: of or pertaining to a funeral or to burial of human remains; as, funerary urn.
Fetor: A strong, offensive smell; stench; fetidness.
federalize: To unite in compact, as different States; to confederate for political purposes; to unite by or under the Federal Constitution.
Flavaniline: A yellow, crystalline, organic dyestuff, C16H14N2, of artifical production. It is a strong base, and is a complex derivative of aniline and quinoline.
freewheeling: acting heedless of consequences; acting without controls, external or internal; as, freewheeling foolishness.
Falstaff: Sir John Falstaff, a celebrated character in Shakespeare's historical play " Henry IV." (1st and 2d parts), and also in " The Merry Wives of Windsor."  He is a very fat, sensual, and witty old knight; a swindler, drunkard, and good-tempered liar; and something of a coward.  Falstaff was originally called Sir John Oldcastle. The first actor of the part was John Heminge.
Fosterer: One who, or that which, fosters.
Footrope: The rope rigged below a yard, upon which men stand when reefing or furling; -- formerly called a horse.
Frequently: At frequent or short intervals; many times; often; repeatedly; commonly.
Forgiving: Disposed to forgive; inclined to overlook offenses; mild; merciful; compassionate; placable; as, a forgiving temper.
Foretaster: One who tastes beforehand, or before another.
Flannel: A soft, nappy, woolen cloth, of loose texture.
Flagstaff: A staff{4} on which a flag is hoisted.
Fluff: To make a mistake in the performance of; -- used mostly of lines in a drama; as, he fluffed the last line of the act.
Friezed: Gathered, or having the map gathered, into little tufts, knots, or protuberances.  Cf. Frieze, v. t., and Friz, v. t., 2.
&Verbar;Fissipedia: A division of the Carnivora, including the dogs, cats, and bears, in which the feet are not webbed; -- opposed to Pinnipedia.
Fibrinoplastic: Like fibrinoplastin; capable of forming fibrin when brought in contact with fibrinogen.
Faucal: Pertaining to the fauces, or opening of the throat; faucial;
Fowler: A sportsman who pursues wild fowl, or takes or kills for food.
&Verbar;Fellah: A peasant or cultivator of the soil among the Egyptians, Syrians, etc.
Friezer: One who, or that which, friezes or frizzes.
Foolish: Marked with, or exhibiting, folly; void of understanding; weak in intellect; without judgment or discretion; silly; unwise.
Fanfaronade: A swaggering; vain boasting; ostentation; a bluster.
fag: a male homosexual; -- always used disparagingly and considered offensive.  Shortened form of faggot.
Farandams: A fabrik made of silk and wool or hair.
Formerly: In time past, either in time immediately preceding or at any indefinite distance; of old; heretofore.
Frounce: A wrinkle, plait, or curl; a flounce; -- also, a frown.
Fume: To expose to the action of fumes; to treat with vapors, smoke, etc.; as, to bleach straw by fuming it with sulphur; to fill with fumes, vapors, odors, etc., as a room.
Facture: The act or manner of making or doing anything; -- now used of a literary, musical, or pictorial production.
Fretwork: Work adorned with frets; ornamental openwork or work in relief, esp. when elaborate and minute in its parts. Hence, any minute play of light and shade, dark and light, or the like.
flyover: the upper level of a crossing of two highways at different levels; called in the United States an overpass; as, an overpass is called a flyover or a flypast in England.
Farfetched: Brought from far, or from a remote place.
Fennel: A perennial plant of the genus Fæniculum (Fæniculum vulgare), having very finely divided leaves.  It is cultivated in gardens for the agreeable aromatic flavor of its seeds.
Felonious: Having the quality of felony; malignant; malicious; villainous; traitorous; perfidious; in a legal sense, done with intent to commit a crime; as, felonious homicide.
Frantic: Mad; raving; furious; violent; wild and disorderly; distracted.
&Verbar;Fibrilla: A minute thread or fiber, as one of the fibrous elements of a muscular fiber; a fibril.
&Verbar;Fiesta: Among Spanish, a religious festival; a saint's day or holiday; also, a holiday or festivity.
Footboy: A page; an attendant in livery; a lackey.
Filial: Of or pertaining to a son or daughter; becoming to a child in relation to his parents; as, filial obedience.
Facework: The material of the outside or front side, as of a wall or building; facing.
Fennec: A small, African, foxlike animal (Vulpes zerda) of a pale fawn color, remarkable for the large size of its ears.
Fissiparous: Reproducing by spontaneous fission. See Fission.
Femoral: Pertaining to the femur or thigh; as, the femoral artery.
Febrile: Pertaining to fever; indicating fever, or derived from it; as, febrile symptoms; febrile action.
Flatiron: An iron with a flat, smooth surface for ironing clothes.
flowers-of-an-hour: An annual weedy herb (Hibiscus trionum) with ephemeral yellow purple-eyed flowers, native to the Old World tropics and naturalized as a weed in North America.
Ferrocyanide: One of a series of complex double cyanides of ferrous iron and some other base.
Flection: The act of bending, or state of being bent.
Flexure: The act of flexing or bending; a turning or curving; flexion; hence, obsequious bowing or bending.
&Verbar;Foulard: A thin, washable material of silk, or silk and cotton, usually with a printed pattern on it.  It was originally imported from India, but now also made elsewhere.
Frisette: a fringe of hair or curls worn about the forehead by women.
Free-milling: Yielding free gold or silver; -- said of certain ores which can be reduced by crushing and amalgamation, without roasting or other chemical treatment.
Frutage: A picture of fruit; decoration by representation of fruit.
Fabrile: Pertaining to a workman, or to work in stone, metal, wood etc.; as, fabrile skill.
Fripper: One who deals in frippery or in old clothes.
&Verbar;Fistularia: A genus of fishes, having the head prolonged into a tube, with the mouth at the extremity.
Fixation: The act of fixing, or the state of being fixed.
Ferrocalcite: Limestone containing a large percentage of iron carbonate, and hence turning brown on exposure.
Flammeous: Pertaining to, consisting of, or resembling, flame.
Fractious: Apt to break out into a passion; apt to scold; cross; snappish; ugly; unruly; as, a fractious man; a fractious horse.
Fumarine: An alkaloid extracted from fumitory, as a white crystalline substance.
Flash burner: A gas burner with a device for lighting by an electric spark.
Fratrage: A sharing among brothers, or brothers' kin.
Firetail: The European redstart; -- called also fireflirt.
Feuillemort: Having the color of a faded leaf.
floorcover: a covering for the floor of an automobile.
firewheel: An annual of the central U. S. (Gaillardia pulchella) having showy long-stalked yellow flower heads marked with scarlet or purple in the center.
Fallow: To plow, harrow, and break up, as land, without seeding, for the purpose of destroying weeds and insects, and rendering it mellow; as, it is profitable to fallow cold, strong, clayey land.
Flittern: A term applied to the bark obtained from young oak trees.
