-fy: A suffix signifying to make, to form into, etc.; as, acetify, amplify, dandify, Frenchify, etc.
farmland: a rural area where farming is practiced; land actually under cultivation or capable of supporting crops.
Flesh: To feed with flesh, as an incitement to further exertion; to initiate; -- from the practice of training hawks and dogs by feeding them with the first game they take, or other flesh. Hence, to use upon flesh (as a murderous weapon) so as to draw blood, especially for the first time.
fretsaw: A narrow-bladed fine-toothed saw for cutting curved outlines.
Falchion: A broad-bladed sword, slightly curved, shorter and lighter than the ordinary sword; -- used in the Middle Ages.
Fold: To confine sheep in a fold.
Fructescence: The maturing or ripening of fruit.
Foreship: The fore part of a ship.
Fortunize: To regulate the fortune of; to make happy.
Folk: In Anglo-Saxon times, the people of a group of townships or villages; a community; a tribe.
firehouse: a building housing firemen and the apparatus they use to extinguish fires.
Fresco: To paint in fresco, as walls.
Fugacious: Flying, or disposed to fly; fleeing away; lasting but a short time; volatile.
Fasciate: Bound with a fillet, sash, or bandage.
flatmate: someone who shares an apartment with a person.
&Verbar;Facul\u00e6: Groups of small shining spots on the surface of the sun which are brighter than the other parts of the photosphere. They are generally seen in the neighborhood of the dark spots, and are supposed to be elevated portions of the photosphere.
Flushing: A heavy, coarse cloth manufactured from shoddy; -- commonly in the &unr_;
Friborg: The pledge and tithing, afterwards called by the Normans frankpledge. See Frankpledge.
Faburden: A species of counterpoint with a drone bass.
Flabbergast: To astonish; to strike with wonder, esp. by extraordinary statements.
Founding: The art of smelting and casting metals.
Fard: To paint; -- said esp. of one's face.
Famosity: The state or quality of being famous.
Floccular: Of or pertaining to the flocculus.
Fayalite: A black, greenish, or brownish mineral of the chrysolite group.  It is a silicate of iron.
Fussy: Making a fuss; disposed to make an unnecessary ado about trifles; overnice; fidgety.
Farm: To engage in the business of tilling the soil; to labor as a farmer.
Faro: A gambling game at cards, in which all the other players play against the dealer or banker, staking their money upon the order in which the cards will lie and be dealt from the pack.
Fissural: Pertaining to a fissure or fissures; as, the fissural pattern of a brain.
Fen: Low land overflowed, or covered wholly or partially with water, but producing sedge, coarse grasses, or other aquatic plants; boggy land; moor; marsh.
Favorable: Full of favor; favoring; manifesting partiality; kind; propitious; friendly.
Frap: To draw together; to bind with a view to secure and strengthen, as a vessel by passing cables around it; to tighten; as a tackle by drawing the lines together.
fire-retardant: able to reduce combustibility or slow the spread of fire; -- of substances that are added to combustible materials to make them less combustible.
Fictile: Molded, or capable of being molded, into form by art; relating to pottery or to molding in any soft material.
Fox: To turn sour; -- said of beer, etc., when it sours in fermenting.
Flagpole sitter: A person who sits for an extended period of time on top of a flagpole or other high column; -- a publicity stunt performed for various reasons.
formalities: a set of procedures required to make a transaction official.
Footpath: A narrow path or way for pedestrains only; a footway.
Forage: To strip of provisions; to supply with forage; as, to forage steeds.
furnishings: the furniture and appliances and other movable accessories (including curtains and rugs) that make a home (or other building) livable.
Formulate: To reduce to, or express in, a formula; to put in a clear and definite form of statement or expression.
Fuse plug: A plug fitted to the fuse hole of a shell to hold the fuse.
Foreshow: To show or exhibit beforehand; to give foreknowledge of; to prognosticate; to foretell.
Friction: The act of rubbing the surface of one body against that of another; attrition; in hygiene, the act of rubbing the body with the hand, with flannel, or with a brush etc., to excite the skin to healthy action.
Ferryboat: A vessel for conveying passengers, merchandise, etc., usually across streams, rivers, bays, and other narrow waters.
Fluidness: The state of being fluid; fluidity.
freewheeler: someone acting freely or even irresponsibly.
Filigree: Relating to, composed of, or resembling, work in filigree; as, a filigree basket. Hence: Fanciful; unsubstantial; merely decorative.
Fletcher: One who fletches or feathers arrows; a manufacturer of bows and arrows.
Flush: So as to be level or even.
Frustrable: Capable of beeing frustrated or defeated.
&Verbar;Frapp\u00e9: Iced; frozen; artificially cooled; as, wine frappé.
Foreside: The front side; the front; esp., a stretch of country fronting the sea.
Flying: Moving in the air with, or as with, wings; moving lightly or rapidly; intended for rapid movement.
follow-through: Carrying a process, plan, or project to full completion; as, I appreciated his follow-through on his promise.  The term usually is used in reference to the period after some point in time at which the actor is given freedom to pursue the project.
fissionable: Capable of undergoing nuclear fission; -- a property of certain isotopes of elements with heavy nuclei.
Formula: A prescribed or set form; an established rule; a fixed or conventional method in which anything is to be done, arranged, or said.
Fascicle: A small bundle or collection; a compact cluster; as, a fascicle of fibers; a fascicle of flowers or roots.
Folder: One who, or that which, folds; esp., a flat, knifelike instrument used for folding paper.
Forgiveness: The act of forgiving; the state of being forgiven; as, the forgiveness of sin or of injuries.
Furfurine: A white, crystalline base, obtained indirectly from furfurol.
Forepossessed: Holding or held formerly in possession.
Fifthly: In the fifth place; as the fifth in order.
Freelance: of or pertaining to a freelance{2}; as, a freelance photographer.
Funny: A clinkerbuit, narrow boat for sculling.
Friesic: The language of the Frisians, a Teutonic people formerly occupying a large part of the coast of Holland and Northwestern Germany. The modern dialects of Friesic are spoken chiefly in the province of Friesland, and on some of the islands near the coast of Germany and Denmark.
free-will: Of or pertaining to free will; voluntary; spontaneous; as, a freewill offering.
Flea: An insect belonging to the genus Pulex, of the order Aphaniptera. Fleas are destitute of wings, but have the power of leaping energetically. The bite is poisonous to most persons. The human flea (Pulex irritans), abundant in Europe, is rare in America, where the dog flea (Ctenocephalides canis, formerly Pulex canis) and the smaller cat flea (Ctenocephalides felis) take its place. See Aphaniptera, and Dog flea. See Illustration in Appendix.
flat-bottom: Having an even lower surface or bottom; as, a flat-bottomed boat.
Flattery: The act or practice of flattering; the act of pleasing by artful commendation or compliments; adulation; false, insincere, or excessive praise.
Flee: To run away, as from danger or evil; to avoid in an alarmed or cowardly manner; to hasten off; -- usually with from. This is sometimes omitted, making the verb transitive.
Fabrication: The act of fabricating, framing, or constructing; construction; manufacture; as, the fabrication of a bridge, a church, or a government.
Flingdust: One who kicks up the dust; a streetwalker; a low manner.
Formulize: To reduce to a formula; to formulate.
Femalize: To make, or to describe as, female or feminine.
Falsification: The act of falsifying, or making false; a counterfeiting; the giving to a thing an appearance of something which it is not.
&Verbar;favella: A group of spores arranged without order and covered with a thin gelatinous envelope, as in certain delicate red algæ.
Fatalistic: Implying, or partaking of the nature of, fatalism.
Figeater: A large beetle (Allorhina nitida) which in the Southern United States destroys figs.  The elytra are velvety green with pale borders.
Flowerpot: A vessel, commonly or earthenware, for earth in which plants are grown.
Frutescent: Somewhat shrubby in character; imperfectly shrubby, as the American species of Wisteria.
Fuzz: To fly off in minute particles.
Freebootery: The act, practice, or gains of a freebooter; freebooting.
Formicidae: The natural family of insects comprising the ants.
firelight: the light of a fire (especially in a fireplace); as, lovers sitting together in the firelight.
fudge factor: a term or factor inserted into a calculation to compensate for anticipated errors, or to arbitrarily make the result conform to some desired conclusion.
fluoridization: the addition of a fluoride to the water supply (to prevent dental decay).
Fright: To alarm suddenly; to shock by causing sudden fear; to terrify; to scare.
Footlight: One of a row of lights in the front of the stage in a theater, etc., and on a level therewith.
Flowerage: State of flowers; flowers, collectively or in general.
Fluo-: A combining form indicating fluorine as an ingredient; as in fluosilicate, fluobenzene.
Fellow: To suit with; to pair with; to match.
Flunlyism: The quality or characteristics of a flunky; readiness to cringe to those who are superior in wealth or position; toadyism.
Forebeam: The breast beam of a loom.
Frostian: of or pertaining to Robert Frost (definition 4).
Follicle: A simple podlike pericarp which contains several seeds and opens along the inner or ventral suture, as in the peony, larkspur and milkweed.
Forceless: Having little or no force; feeble.
Flue pipe: A pipe, esp. an organ pipe, whose tone is produced by the impinging of a current of air upon an edge, or lip, causing a wave motion in the air within; a mouth pipe; -- distinguished from reed pipe. Flue pipes are either open or closed (stopped at the distant end). The flute and flageolet are open pipes; a bottle acts as a closed pipe when one blows across the neck. The organ has both open and closed flue pipes, those of metal being usually round in section, and those of wood triangular or square.
Funicle: A small cord, ligature, or fiber.
Foumart: The European polecat; -- called also European ferret, and fitchew. See Polecat.
Flucan: Soft clayey matter in the vein, or surrounding it.
Farsighted: Seeing to great distance; hence, of good judgment regarding the remote effects of actions; sagacious.
Foursome: A game between four players, with two on each side and each side playing but one ball, the partners striking alternately.  It is called a mixed foursome when each side consists of a man and a woman.
fair-and-square: fair and honest; just.  Opposite of unfair.
Following: Next after; succeeding; ensuing; as, the assembly was held on the following day.
&Verbar;Fantoccini: Puppets caused to perform evolutions or dramatic scenes by means of machinery; also, the representations in which they are used.
Fleshiness: The state of being fleshy; plumpness; corpulence; grossness.
Free-spoken: Accustomed to speak without reserve; willing to speak out without subtlety.
Fibrillous: Pertaining to, or composed of, fibers.
&Verbar;Fiacre: A kind of French hackney coach.
Fanatical: Characteristic of, or relating to, fanaticism; fanatic.
Forlay: To lie in wait for; to ambush.
fiberglass: a material made of fine glass fibers woven into a fabric-like form, and used in applications requiring heat resistance; it is also embedded in resins to make a pliable but strong composite material used as the main component of fishing rods and boat hulls, and replacing the sheet metal in some automobile bodies.
Faint-hearted: Wanting in courage; depressed by fear; easily discouraged or frightened; cowardly; timorous; dejected.
Four-in-hand: Consisting of four horses controlled by one person; as, a four-in-hand team; drawn by four horses driven by one person; as, a four-in-hand coach.
Failure: Cessation of supply, or total defect; a failing; deficiency; as, failure of rain; failure of crops.
futharc: the name for the runic alphabet.  See rune.
Foretime: The past; the time before the present.
filmmake: to make films; be a film maker.
Flatting: The process or operation of making flat, as a cylinder of glass by opening it out.
Feather-edged: Having a feather-edge; also, having one edge thinner than the other, as a board; -- in the United States, said only of stuff one edge of which is made as thin as practicable.
Fundable: Capable of being funded, or converted into a fund; convertible into bonds.
Farseeing: Able to see to a great distance; farsighted.
Finnish: Of or pertaining to Finland, to the Finns, or to their language.
&Verbar;Fritillaria: A genus of liliaceous plants, of which the crown-imperial (Fritillaria imperialis) is one species, and the Guinea-hen flower (F. Meleagris) another. See Crown-imperial.
Frondose: Frond bearing; resembling a frond; having a simple expansion not separable into stem and leaves.
fallout: the radioactive particles that settle to the ground after a nuclear explosion.
familial: relating to or having the characteristics of a family; as, children of the same familial background; familial aggregation.
Flexile: Flexible; pliant; pliable; easily bent; plastic; tractable.
Fertility: The state or quality of being fertile or fruitful; fruitfulness; productiveness; fecundity; richness; abundance of resources; fertile invention; quickness; readiness; as, the fertility of soil, or of imagination.
Fatten: To grow fat or corpulent; to grow plump, thick, or fleshy; to be pampered.
four-ply: having a thickness made up of four layers or strands; as, four-ply yarns.
Fleury: Finished at the ends with fleurs-de-lis; -- said esp. of a cross so decorated.
Forger: One who forges, makes, of forms; a fabricator; a falsifier.
Forget: To lose the remembrance of; to let go from the memory; to cease to have in mind; not to think of; also, to lose the power of; to cease from doing.
Fatherlessness: The state of being without a father.
Fumigatory: Having the quality of purifying by smoke.
Frank-marriage: A certain tenure in tail special; an estate of inheritance given to a man his wife (the wife being of the blood of the donor), and descendible to the heirs of their two bodies begotten.
firebush: An evergreen South American shrub *Streptosolen jamesonii) having showy trumpet-shaped orange flowers; grown as an ornamental or houseplant.
Finely: In a fine or finished manner.
Furnisher: One who supplies or fits out.
&Verbar;Fingrigo: A prickly, climbing shrub of the genus Pisonia. The fruit is a kind of berry.
&Verbar;Frutex: A plant having a woody, durable stem, but less than a tree; a shrub.
&Verbar;Fibrospongi\u00e6: An order of sponges having a fibrous skeleton, including the commercial sponges.
&Verbar;Ficus: A genus of trees or shrubs, one species of which (F. Carica) produces the figs of commerce; the fig tree.
&Verbar;Floccus: The tuft of hair terminating the tail of mammals.
Fluxible: Capable of being melted or fused, as a mineral.
FIFO: an accounting method in which goods in inventory are valued at the price of the most recent acquisition of each type of goods, and those used up from inventory are valued at the cost of those first acquired.
Fahlunite: A hydrated silica of alumina, resulting from the alteration of iolite.
Feminineness: The quality of being feminine; womanliness; womanishness.
free association: The act or process of free-associating. It is a technique used in psychoanalysis and is supposed to allow the analyst access to the unconscious thoughts of the analysand.  See free-associate.
feedbag: a canvas bag that is used to feed an animal (such as a horse or mule); animal feed such as oats are placed in the bag, and it is fastened at the top of the head, covering the muzzle.  The animal may then eat the contents while thus wearing the feedbag.
freeze-dried: dried by freezing and applying a vacuum; -- used of tissue or blood or serum or other biological substances.
Fixative: That which serves to set or fix colors or drawings, as a mordant.
Founder: A lameness in the foot of a horse, occasioned by inflammation; closh.
Favoritism: The disposition to favor and promote the interest of one person or family, or of one class of men, to the neglect of others having equal claims; partiality.
Factoress: A factor who is a woman.
futz: To fool around; to act without plan or purpose; -- usually used with around; as, don't futz around with a device without understanding its operation.
favor: Kind regard; propitious aspect; countenance; friendly disposition; kindness; good will.
Fecundity: The quality or power of producing fruit; fruitfulness; especially (Biol.), the quality in female organisms of reproducing rapidly and in great numbers.
fluorochrome: Any of various fluorescent substances used in fluorescence microscopy to stain specimens.
Figurant: One who dances at the opera, not singly, but in groups or figures; an accessory character on the stage, who figures in its scenes, but has nothing to say; hence, one who figures in any scene, without taking a prominent part.
Farmyard: The yard or inclosure attached to a barn, or the space inclosed by the farm buildings.
Finitely: In a finite manner or degree.
Foxery: Behavior like that of a fox; cunning.
Fleece: To deprive of a fleece, or natural covering of wool.
Firebote: An allowance of fuel. See Bote.
Fee-faw-fum: A nonsensical exclamation attributed to giants and ogres; hence, any expression calculated to impose upon the timid and ignorant.
Forum: A market place or public place in Rome, where causes were judicially tried, and orations delivered to the people.
foldable: Capable of being folded into a more compact form.
Fossilism: The science or state of fossils.
Firedog: A support for wood in a fireplace; an andiron.
Facing: A covering in front, for ornament or other purpose; an exterior covering or sheathing; as, the facing of an earthen slope, sea wall, etc. , to strengthen it or to protect or adorn the exposed surface.
fledgeless: not equipped with feathers; -- of an arrow.
Forefinger: The finger next to the thumb; the index finger.
Flock: To coat with flock, as wall paper; to roughen the surface of (as glass) so as to give an appearance of being covered with fine flock.
frat house: a house used by a chapter of a fraternity at a college.
Fescue: To use a fescue, or teach with a fescue.
Formidable: Exciting fear or apprehension; impressing dread; adapted to excite fear and deter from approach, encounter, or undertaking; alarming.
Fluviograph: An instrument for measuring and recording automatically the rise and fall of a river.
Formosan: of, pertaining to, or characteristic of, Formosa or the natives of Formosa; as, The native Formosan population now forms a minority on their own island..
Fluctuability: The capacity or ability to fluctuate.
Fossilist: One who is versed in the science of fossils; a paleontologist.
focsle: The forecastle, a superstructure in the bow of a merchant ship where the crew is housed; -- the spelling is intended to reflect the common pronunciation among seamen.
Frame-up: A conspiracy or plot for a malicious or evil purpose;
Flea-beetle: A small beetle of the family Halticidæ, of many species. They have strong posterior legs and leap like fleas. The turnip flea-beetle (Phyllotreta vittata) and that of the grapevine (Graptodera chalybea) are common injurious species.
Fillet: To bind, furnish, or adorn with a fillet.
Fiction: The act of feigning, inventing, or imagining; as, by a mere fiction of the mind.
Flimsiness: The state or quality of being flimsy.
frisking: The act or process of searching someone for concealed weapons.
Fabler: A writer of fables; a fabulist; a dealer in untruths or falsehoods.
Fibrous: Containing, or consisting of, fibers; as, the fibrous coat of the cocoanut; the fibrous roots of grasses.
&Verbar;Fibroma: A tumor consisting mainly of fibrous tissue, or of same modification of such tissue.
Fenestral: A casement or window sash, closed with cloth or paper instead of glass.
Fissigemmation: A process of reproduction intermediate between fission and gemmation.
Forfeiter: One who incurs a penalty of forfeiture.
Fungus: Any one of the Fungi, a large and very complex group of thallophytes of low organization, -- the molds, mildews, rusts, smuts, mushrooms, toadstools, puff balls, and the allies of each.  See fungi.
Futurable: Capable of being future; possible to occur.
&Verbar;Fenestra: A small opening; esp., one of the apertures, closed by membranes, between the tympanum and internal ear.
Faultless: Without fault; not defective or imperfect; free from blemish; free from incorrectness, vice, or offense; perfect; as, a faultless poem.
Freebooting: Acting the freebooter; practicing freebootery; robbing.
&Verbar;Format: The shape and size of a book or other printed publication; hence, its external form.
Flora: The goddess of flowers and spring.
Fabulist: One who invents or writes fables.
Flapper: One who, or that which, flaps.
Fermentation tank: a tank in which fermentations are carried out.
foreshore: the part of the seashore between the high-water and and low-water marks.
Footed: Having a foot or feet; shaped in the foot; as, a footed candlestick.
Flat-cap: A kind of low-crowned cap formerly worn by all classes in England, and continued in London after disuse elsewhere; -- hence, a citizen of London.
Featherbone: A substitute for whalebone, made from the quills of geese and turkeys.
Filander: A species of kangaroo (Macropus Brunii), inhabiting New Guinea.
Foregleam: An antecedent or premonitory gleam; a dawning light.
Frostless: Free from frost; as, a frostless winter.
Flatwise: With the flat side downward, or next to another object; not edgewise.
Fief: An estate held of a superior on condition of military service; a fee; a feud. See under Benefice, n., 2.
Fornicator: An unmarried person, male or female, who has criminal intercourse with the other sex; one guilty of fornication.
&Verbar;Fremitus: Palpable vibration or thrill; as, the rhonchial fremitus.
Farmhouse: A dwelling house on a farm; a farmer's residence.
fieldsman: a member of the cricket team that is fielding rather than batting.
friendly fire: Weapons fire{9}, such as artillery or aerial bombardment, from one's own forces; -- used mostly when troops do damage or cause casualties among their own forces; as, the tank was hit by friendly fire.
Fluctuation: A motion like that of waves; a moving in this and that direction; as, the fluctuations of the sea.
Fonde: To endeavor; to strive; to try.
Frost-blite: A plant of the genus Atriplex; orache.
&Verbar;Fa\u00e7ade: The front of a building; esp., the principal front, having some architectural pretensions. Thus a church is said to have its façade unfinished, though the interior may be in use.
&Verbar;Feuilleton: A part of a French newspaper (usually the bottom of the page), devoted to light literature, criticism, etc.; also, the article or tale itself, thus printed.
Fitch: The European polecat; also, its fur.
Franking: A method of forming a joint at the intersection of window-sash bars, by cutting away only enough wood to show a miter.
Flatulently: In a flatulent manner; with flatulence.
Folium: A leaf, esp. a thin leaf or plate.
Fumade: A salted and smoked fish, as the pilchard.
Fringillidae: A natural family of birds of the finch group having short conical bills adapted for eating seeds, including finches, goldfinches, bullfinches, chaffinches, siskins, canaries, cardinals, grosbeaks, crossbills, linnets, and buntings.  This family at one time included the sparrows of the family Emberizinae, but has more recently been restricted in usage.
Fishhawk: The osprey (Pandion haliaëtus), found both in Europe and America; -- so called because it plunges into the water and seizes fishes in its talons. Called also fishing eagle, and bald buzzard.
Farce: Stuffing, or mixture of viands, like that used on dressing a fowl; forcemeat.
Fatness: The quality or state of being fat, plump, or full-fed; corpulency; fullness of flesh.
Feretory: A portable bier or shrine, variously adorned, used for containing relics of saints.
Fortitude: Power to resist attack; strength; firmness.
Farcy: A contagious disease of horses, associated with painful ulcerating enlargements, esp. upon the head and limbs. It is of the same nature as glanders, and is often fatal. Called also farcin, and farcimen.
foregone conclusion: An inevitable outcome; a certain result; a certainty.
Friendly: A friendly person; -- usually applied to natives friendly to foreign settlers or invaders.
Forcipation: Torture by pinching with forceps or pinchers.
Fever: To put into a fever; to affect with fever; as, a fevered lip.
Ferricyanide: One of a complex series of double cyanides of ferric iron and some other base.
Fourierism: The coöperative socialistic system of Charles Fourier, a Frenchman, who recommended the reorganization of society into small communities, living in common.
Fourierist: One who adopts the views of Fourier.
Frigid: Cold; wanting heat or warmth; of low temperature; as, a frigid climate.
&Verbar;Fugato: in the gugue style, but not strictly like a fugue.
Frank-chase: The liberty or franchise of having a chase; free chase.
Function: To execute or perform a function; to transact one's regular or appointed business.
Funge: A blockhead; a dolt; a fool.
Footmark: A footprint; a track or vestige.
Foxlike: Resembling a fox in his characteristic qualities; cunning; artful; foxy.
Fragaria: a genus of plants comprising the strawberry plants.
Flapdragon: To swallow whole, as a flapdragon; to devour.
Fulmine: To shoot; to dart like lightning; to fulminate; to utter with authority or vehemence.
Fourpence: A British silver coin, worth four pence; a groat.
Foremostly: In the foremost place or order; among the foremost.
Fenianism: The principles, purposes, and methods of the Fenians.
Fowl: To catch or kill wild fowl, for game or food, as by shooting, or by decoys, nets, etc.
Faun: A god of fields and shipherds, diddering little from the satyr. The fauns are usually represented as half goat and half man.
Focimeter: An assisting instrument for focusing an object in or before a camera.
Fleecy: Covered with, made of, or resembling, a fleece.
Fantasy: To have a fancy for; to be pleased with; to like; to fancy.
Fantast: One whose manners or ideas are fantastic.
Fishlike: Like fish; suggestive of fish; having some of the qualities of fish.
&Verbar;Figurine: A very small figure, whether human or of an animal; especially, one in terra cotta or the like; -- distinguished from statuette, which is applied to small figures in bronze, marble, etc.
Faithful: Full of faith, or having faith; disposed to believe, especially in the declarations and promises of God.
Filipendulous: Suspended by, or strung upon, a thread; -- said of tuberous swellings in the middle or at the extremities of slender, threadlike rootlets.
Floriken: An Indian bustard (Otis aurita). The Bengal floriken is Sypheotides Bengalensis.
firebrick: a brick made of fire clay, used for lining e.g. furnaces and chimneys.
frogmarch: to march a person against his will by any method.
Fowlerite: A variety of rhodonite, from Franklin Furnace, New Jersey, containing some zinc.
Fencible: A soldier enlisted for home service only; -- usually in the pl.
Five-leafed: Having five leaflets, as the Virginia creeper.
flywheel: A heavy wheel or disk which stores kinetic energy by rotating on a shaft, and by its momentum smoothes the operation of a reciprocating engine by reducing fluctuations of speed.  It is used in certain types of machinery, such as automobiles.
Fourth: One of four equal parts into which one whole may be divided; the quotient of a unit divided by four.
&Verbar;Fissurella: A genus of marine gastropod mollusks, having a conical or limpetlike shell, with an opening at the apex; -- called also keyhole limpet.
Filoselle: A kind of silk thread less glossy than floss, and spun from coarser material. It is much used in embroidery instead of floss.
fire hydrant: an upright hydrant that can supply large volumes of water to use in fighting a fire.  They are commonly placed at intervals at the street edge of a sidewalk, spaced for convenience in suppressing fires in towns.
&Verbar;Fronde: A political party in France, during the minority of Louis XIV., who opposed the government, and made war upon the court party.
Flutterer: One who, or that which, flutters.
Flying lemur: either of two nocturnal lemurlike mammals inhabiting the East Indies (Cynocephalus variegatus) or the Phillipines (Cynocephalus volans) having broad folds of skin between the fore and hind limbs on both sides of the body allowing them to make long gliding leaps; they have been classed in the separate order Dermoptera.  They are arboreal and have become rare.
Flowen: imp. pl. of Fly, v. i.
flashlight: a portable battery-powered electric lamp, small enough to be held in one hand; -- it is most commonly cylindrical, but other forms are also made.  It is called in Britain a torch
Fluoboric: Pertaining to, derived from, or consisting of, fluorine and boron.
Fay: To lie close together; to fit; to fadge; -- often with in, into, with, or together.
Foredate: To date before the true time; to antedate.
Far: To a great extent or distance of space; widely; as, we are separated far from each other.
Fieldwork: Any temporary fortification thrown up by an army in the field; -- commonly in the plural.
Fluxional: Pertaining to, or having the nature of, fluxion or fluxions; variable; inconstant.
Fat: To grow fat, plump, and fleshy.
Foible: A moral weakness; a failing; a weak point; a frailty.
Functionary: One charged with the performance of a function or office; as, a public functionary; secular functionaries.
Fan: To move as with a fan.
Ferrous: Pertaining to, or derived from, iron; -- especially used of compounds of iron in which the iron has its lower valence of two; as, ferrous sulphate.
Fugleman: A soldier especially expert and well drilled, who takes his place in front of a military company, as a guide for the others in their exercises; a file leader. He originally stood in front of the right wing.
french-fry: to cook by immersing in hot fat.
Fac: A large ornamental letter used, esp. by the early printers, at the commencement of the chapters and other divisions of a book.
Filthy: Defiled with filth, whether material or moral; nasty; dirty; polluted; foul; impure; obscene.
Fag: To tire by labor; to exhaust; as, he was almost fagged out.
Faller: One who, or that which, falls.
fluctuating: moving irregularly in an oscillatory manner, especially up and down; as, fluctuating prices.
Futhorc: The Runic alphabet; -- so called from the first six letters f, u, þ (th), o (or a), r, c (=k).  See futharc.
Forswear: To swear falsely; to commit perjury.
fledgling: having just acquired its flight feathers; -- of a young bird; as, a fledgling robin.
Fittedness: The state or quality of being fitted; adaptation.
Fallen: Dropped; prostrate; degraded; ruined; decreased; dead.
Froterer: One who frotes; one who rubs or chafes.
Fibroin: A variety of gelatin; the chief ingredient of raw silk, extracted as a white amorphous mass.
Forestry: The art of forming or of cultivating forests; the management of growing timber.
Fortalice: A small outwork of a fortification; a fortilage; -- called also fortelace.
Fashion: To form; to give shape or figure to; to mold.
Fling: A cast from the hand; a throw; also, a flounce; a kick; as, the fling of a horse.
Filefish: Any plectognath fish of the genera Monacanthus, Alutera, balistes, and allied genera; -- so called on account of the roughly granulated skin, which is sometimes used in place of sandpaper.
Fichu: A light cape, usually of lace, worn by women, to cover the neck and throat, and extending to the shoulders.
Finfoot: A South American bird (Heliornis fulica) allied to the grebes. The name is also applied to several related species of the genus Podica.
Free-lover: One who believes in or practices free-love.
Frosted: Covered with hoarfrost or anything resembling hoarfrost; ornamented with frosting; also, frost-bitten; as, a frosted cake; frosted donuts.
Furoin: A colorless, crystalline substance, C10H8O4, from furfurol.
Five-twenties: Five-twenty bonds of the United States (bearing six per cent interest), issued in 1862, '64, and '65, redeemable after five and payable in twenty years.
Fear: To be in apprehension of evil; to be afraid; to feel anxiety on account of some expected evil.
Free-living: Unrestrained indulgence of the appetites as a way of life.
Feat: Dexterous in movements or service; skillful; neat; nice; pretty.
Fox-hunting: Pertaining to or engaged in the hunting of foxes; fond of hunting foxes.
Fleetings: A mixture of buttermilk and boiling whey; curds.
Forest: To cover with trees or wood.
&Verbar;Finochio: An umbelliferous plant (Fœniculum dulce) having a somewhat tuberous stem; sweet fennel. The blanched stems are used in France and Italy as a culinary vegetable.
Frenchism: A French mode or characteristic; an idiom peculiar to the French language.
Folio: Formed of sheets each folded once, making two leaves, or four pages; as, a folio volume. See Folio, n., 3.
Flint glass: A soft, heavy, brilliant glass, consisting essentially of a silicate of lead and potassium. It is used for tableware, and for optical instruments, as prisms, its density giving a high degree of dispersive power; -- so called, because formerly the silica was obtained from pulverized flints. Called also crystal glass.  Cf. Glass.
Flybane: A kind of catchfly of the genus Silene; also, a poisonous mushroom (Agaricus muscarius); fly agaric.
footage: the amount of film that has been shot.
Flute: To play, whistle, or sing with a clear, soft note, like that of a flute.
Forte: The strong point; that in which one excels.
faraday: the quantity of electric charge that, passed though an ionic solution, will cause electrolysis of one equivalent of ions; it is equal to about 96,490 coulombs.  The number of univalent metal ions (such as silver in a silver nitrate solution) which would be deposited as free metal by such a current is Avogadro's number, 6.023 x 1023.
Frondent: Covered with leaves; leafy; as, a frondent tree.
Fomentation: The act of fomenting; the application of warm, soft, medicinal substances, as for the purpose of easing pain, by relaxing the skin, or of discussing tumors.
Forth: A way; a passage or ford.
Fiftieth: One of fifty equal parts; the quotient of a unit divided by fifty.
Firefly: Any luminous winged insect, esp. luminous beetles of the family Lampyridæ.
Formally: In a formal manner; essentially; characteristically; expressly; regularly; ceremoniously; precisely.
Flite: Strife; dispute; abusive or upbraiding talk, as in fliting; wrangling.
Fracid: Rotten from being too ripe; overripe.
Ferro-concrete: Concrete strengthened by a core or foundation skeleton of iron or steel bars, strips, etc. Floors, columns, piles, water pipes, etc., have been successfully made of it. Called also armored concrete steel, and most commonly reenforced concrete.
Flare-up: A sudden burst of anger or passion; an angry dispute.
Fuze: A tube, filled with combustible matter, for exploding a shell, etc. See Fuse, n.
Felsite: A finegrained rock, flintlike in fracture, consisting essentially of orthoclase feldspar with occasional grains of quartz.
Fastening: Anything that binds and makes fast, as a lock, catch, bolt, bar, buckle, etc.
Fluctuate: To cause to move as a wave; to put in motion.
Fullonical: Pertaining to a fuller of cloth.
Functionalize: To assign to some function or office.
fledgeling: a new member of a group.
fellatio: a form of sexual activity between two persons in which the penis of one is stimulated by the other's mouth, especially until orgasm is achieved.  It is a form of oral sex.  Compare cunnilingus.  The act is also called by the slang term blow job.
fingerstall: a sheath worn to protect a finger.
fray: An angry quarrel; an affray; contest; combat; broil.
Forkiness: The quality or state or dividing in a forklike manner.
Fleeting: Passing swiftly away; not durable; transient; transitory; as, the fleeting hours or moments.
Fetus: The young or embryo of a vertebrate animal in the womb, or in the egg; often restricted to the later stages in the development of viviparous and oviparous animals. showing the main recognizable features of the mature animal, embryo being applied to the earlier stages.
Frangibility: The state or quality of being frangible.
Foreclosure: The act or process of foreclosing; a proceeding which bars or extinguishes a mortgager's right of redeeming a mortgaged estate.
Frighten: To disturb with fear; to throw into a state of alarm or fright; to affright; to terrify.
Fishgig: A spear with barbed prongs used for harpooning fish.
feuter: To set close; to fix in rest, as a spear.
furred: covered with a dense coat of fine silky hairs.
Four-oclock: A plant of the genus Mirabilis. There are about half a dozen species, natives of the warmer parts of America. The common four-o'clock is M. Jalapa. Its flowers are white, yellow, and red, and open toward sunset, or earlier in cloudy weather; hence the name. It is also called marvel of Peru, and afternoon lady.
Fable: To feign; to invent; to devise, and speak of, as true or real; to tell of falsely.
Flavin: A yellow, vegetable dyestuff, resembling quercitron.
Fissipalmate: Semipalmate and loboped, as a grebe's foot. See Illust. under Aves.
Filoplumaceous: Having the structure of a filoplume.
Frapping: A lashing binding a thing tightly or binding things together.
Fuliginous: Pertaining to soot; sooty; dark; dusky.
Flyblow: One of the eggs or young larvæ deposited by a flesh fly, or blowfly.
Figurehead: The figure, statue, or bust, on the prow of a ship.
Fenestration: The arrangement and proportioning of windows; -- used by modern writers for the decorating of an architectural composition by means of the window (and door) openings, their ornaments, and proportions.
Foxy: Like or pertaining to the fox; foxlike in disposition or looks; wily; cunning.
Frostweed: An American species of rockrose (Helianthemum Canadense), sometimes used in medicine as an astringent or aromatic tonic.
Filar: Of or pertaining to a thread or line; characterized by threads stretched across the field of view; as, a filar microscope; a filar micrometer.
Five: The number next greater than four, and less than six; five units or objects.
facilitative: freeing from difficulty or impediment; as, facilitative changes in the economic structure.
Finance: To conduct the finances of; to provide for, and manage, the capital for; to financier.
firefighter: A person whose occupation it is to go to the scene of an unwanted fire and extinguish it; a member of a fire company; a fireman{1} or a woman who fights fires.
fussbudget: a person who thinks excessively about unfortunate things that might happen; one who is excessively concerned about matters of trifling importance.
Faradism: The treatment with faradic or induced currents of electricity for remedial purposes.
Femininity: The quality or nature of the female sex; womanliness.
&Verbar;Fils: Son; -- sometimes used after a French proper name to distinguish a son from his father, as, Alexandre Dumas, fils.
Fraternization: The act of fraternizing or uniting as brothers.
Frowey: Working smoothly, or without splitting; -- said of timber.
Foralite: A tubelike marking, occuring in sandstone and other strata.
Feather-foil: An aquatic plant (Hottonia palustris), having finely divided leaves.
Flamy: Flaming; blazing; flamelike; flame-colored; composed of flame.
Flying fish: A fish which is able to leap from the water, and fly a considerable distance by means of its large and long pectoral fins. These fishes belong to several species of the genus Exocœtus, and are found in the warmer parts of all the oceans.
Freshen: To grow fresh; to lose saltness.
Fitchet: The European polecat (Putorius fœtidus). See Polecat.
Flame: To kindle; to inflame; to excite.
Figwort: A genus of herbaceous plants (Scrophularia), mostly found in the north temperate zones. See Brownwort.
Fantasia: A continuous composition, not divided into what are called movements, or governed by the ordinary rules of musical design, but in which the author's fancy roves unrestricted by set form.
Forky: Opening into two or more parts or shoots; forked; furcated.
fragmentation: the act or process of separating something into small pieces or fine particles.
Fichtelite: A white crystallized mineral resin from the Fichtelgebirge, Bavaria.
Fenks: The refuse whale blubber, used as a manure, and in the manufacture of Prussian blue.
Foolscap: A writing paper made in sheets, ordinarily 16 x 13 inches, and folded so as to make a page 13 x 8 inches. See Paper.
Falsity: The quality of being false; coutrariety or want of conformity to truth.
Fleme: To banish; to drive out; to expel.
Footbridge: A narrow bridge for foot passengers only.
Ferro-: A prefix, or combining form, indicating ferrous iron as an ingredient; as, ferrocyanide.
Formulation: The act, process, or result of formulating or reducing to a formula.
&Verbar;Flagellata: An order of Infusoria, having one or two long, whiplike cilia, at the anterior end. It includes monads. See Infusoria, and Monad.
faggot: a male homosexual; -- always used disparagingly and considered offensive.
Fiber-faced: Having a visible fiber embodied in the surface of; -- applied esp. to a kind of paper for checks, drafts, etc.
Fidejussor: A surety; one bound for another, conjointly with him; a guarantor.
Forbearing: Disposed or accustomed to forbear; patient; long-suffering.
Fraught: To freight; to load; to burden; to fill; to crowd.
Flocculent: Clothed with small flocks or flakes; woolly.
Furrier: A dealer in furs; one who makes or sells fur goods.
Flautist: A player on the flute; a flutist.
first-year: Being in the first year of an experience especially in a U. S. high school or college; -- of a person.
Fortunate: Coming by good luck or favorable chance; bringing some good thing not foreseen as certain; presaging happiness; auspicious; as, a fortunate event; a fortunate concurrence of circumstances; a fortunate investment.
Frugality: The quality of being frugal; prudent economy; that careful management of anything valuable which expends nothing unnecessarily, and applies what is used to a profitable purpose; thrift; --- opposed to extravagance.
form-only: being a matter of form only; lacking substance.
Fate: A fixed decree by which the order of things is prescribed; the immutable law of the universe; inevitable necessity; the force by which all existence is determined and conditioned.
Fertilization: The act or process of rendering fertile.
Forkbeard: A European fish (Raniceps raninus), having a large flat head; -- also called tadpole fish, and lesser forked beard.
Feather-veined: Having the veins (of a leaf) diverging from the two sides of a midrib.
Fatigue: To weary with labor or any bodily or mental exertion; to harass with toil; to exhaust the strength or endurance of; to tire.
Finder: One who, or that which, finds;
fizzle: A failure or abortive effort; a fiasco.
&Verbar;Furioso: With great force or vigor; vehemently.
February: The second month in the year, said to have been introduced into the Roman calendar by Numa. In common years this month contains twenty-eight days; in the bissextile, or leap year, it has twenty-nine days.
Fibrochondrosteal: Partly fibrous, partly cartilaginous, and partly osseous.
Futurism: A movement or phase of post-impressionism (which see, below).
Frangible: Capable of being broken; brittle; fragile; easily broken.
Fregatidae: A natural family including the genus Fregata, of frigate birds.
Footstall: The stirrup of a woman's saddle.
Footstalk: The stalk of a leaf or of flower; a petiole, pedicel, or reduncle.
Fermentation: The process of undergoing an effervescent change, as by the action of yeast;
Fluework: A general name for organ stops in which the sound is caused by wind passing through a flue or fissure and striking an edge above; -- in distinction from reedwork.
Fourscore: The product of four times twenty; eighty units or objects.
Fosseway: One of the great military roads constructed by the Romans in England and other parts of Europe; -- so called from the fosse or ditch on each side for keeping it dry.
&Verbar;Fasciola: A band of gray matter bordering the fimbria in the brain; the dentate convolution.
Ferruginous: Partaking of iron; containing particles of iron.
fall webworm: The larva of any moth of the genus Hyphantria, which spins a web around the foliage on which it feeds.
Flasket: A long, shallow basket, with two handles.
Fourteenth: One of fourteen equal parts into which one whole may be divided; the quotient of a unit divided by fourteen.
Futurist: One whose chief interests are in what is to come; one who anxiously, eagerly, or confidently looks forward to the future; an expectant.
Fading: An Irish dance; also, the burden of a song.
